10724224914/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1011&page=12 22], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1010&page=20 22], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509113357/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1005&page=22 23], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1009&page=20 23], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721212216/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1008&page=20 24], [https://web.archive.org/web/20081014094635/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1010&page=22 24], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224944/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1009&page=20 25], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724225128/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1012&page=22 26], [http://adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1010&page=20 27], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080803092414/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1008&page=20 27], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1005&page=20 28]\n* ''Spectrum'' 8:4 (August 1977) [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202162437/http://spectrummagazine.org/spectrum/issue/vol_8_no_4_aug_1977 Special Section: An Adventist Creed?]\n* \"[http://docs.adventistarchives.org/docs/RH/RH19840712-V161-28__B.pdf  Why Seventh-day Adventists have no creed]\" (DjVu) by [[Arthur L. White]]. ''Adventist Review'' 161:28 (12 July 1984), pp 6\u20138\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080821132246/http://spectrummagazine.org/files/archive/archive11-15/11-1report.pdf  General Conference Report]\" section, by Lawrence Geraty and other authors. ''Spectrum'' 11:1 (July 1980)  ([https://web.archive.org/web/20090611025007/http://www.spectrummagazine.org/blog/2009/06/07/new_statement_fundamental_beliefs reprint] of Geraty article)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080829163338/http://www.spectrummagazine.org/files/archive/archive11-15/11-3responses.pdf Letters to the editor] in ''Spectrum'' 11:3 (February 1981), pp 61\u2014\n* \"Creeds and Statements of Belief in Early Adventist Thought\" by S. Joseph Kidder. ''[[Andrews University Seminary Studies]]'' 47:1 (Spring 2009), pp 101\u201316\n* [http://jewel.andrews.edu:82/search/dCreeds Search for \"Creeds\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} in the Seventh-day Adventist Periodical Index (SDAPI)\n\n[[Category:Seventh-day Adventist theology|Fundamentals, 28]]\n[[Category:Christian statements of faith]]\n[[Category:1980 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:1980 documents]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian texts]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Core beliefs of the Seventh-day Adventist Church}}\n{{Seventh-day Adventism}}\n\nThe '''28 fundamental beliefs''' are the core beliefs of [[Seventh-day Adventist theology]]. Adventists are opposed to the formulation of [[creed]]s, so the 28 fundamental beliefs are considered ''descriptors'', not ''prescriptors''; that is, that they describe the official position of the church but are not criteria for membership. These beliefs were originally known as the '''27 fundamental beliefs''' when adopted by the church's [[General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|General Conference]] in 1999 additional belief (number 11) was added in 2005.<ref>{{cite news\n |url=http://news.adventist.org/specials/2005/gcsession/voted_docs/growinginchrist.html \n |title=Growing in Christ \n |accessdate=2006-05-26 \n |date=2005-07-04 \n |publisher=[[Adventist News Network]] \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20051129114541/http://news.adventist.org/specials/2005/gcsession/voted_docs/growinginchrist.html \n |archivedate=2005-11-29 \n |url-status=dead \n |df= \n}}</ref>  The ''Seventh-day Adventist Bible Commentary'' is a significant expression of Adventist theological thought.\n\nThey may be grouped into the doctrines of God, humanity, salvation, the church, Christian life, and the restoration.<ref>[http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/index.html Seventh-day Adventist Church] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060310104717/http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/index.html |date=2006-03-10 }} Fundamental Beliefs</ref>\n\n==History==\n{{Prose|section|small=left|date=December 2017}}\n[[Image:SDAs believe.jpg|right|thumb|200px|''Seventh-day Adventists Believe'' (2nd edition 2005), official publication explaining the fundamental beliefs of the Seventh-day Adventist church.]]\nAdventists have historically been reluctant to formalize a creed. In the October 8, 1861 [[Adventist Review|Review and Herald]], [[J. N. Loughborough]] wrote:\n:\"The first step of apostasy is to get up a creed, telling us what we shall believe. The second is, to make that creed a test of fellowship. The third is to try members by that creed. The fourth to denounce as heretics those who do not believe that creed. And fifth, to commence persecution against such.\"<ref>{{Cite journal\n |last=Bates \n |first=Joseph \n |author-link=Joseph Bates (Adventist) \n |last2=Smith \n |first2=Uriah \n |author2-link=Uriah Smith \n |title=Doings of the Battle Creek Conference, Oct. 5 & 6, 1861 \n |journal=[[Adventist Review|Review and Herald]] \n |volume=18 \n |issue=19 \n |pages=148 \n |date=1861-10-08 \n |url=http://www.adventistarchives.org/docs/RH/RH1861-V18-19/index.djvu \n |format=DJVU \n |id= \n |accessdate=2006-11-06 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927230759/http://www.adventistarchives.org/docs/RH/RH1861-V18-19/index.djvu \n |archivedate=2007-09-27 \n}}</ref>\n\nSeveral summaries of Adventist theology have been presented at various times.\n\n* In 1872 a pamphlet was produced presenting twenty-five ''Fundamental Principles''<ref>[http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/index.html/ Fundamental Beliefs<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> not to \"secure uniformity\" but \"to meet inquiries\" and \"to correct false statements.\"<ref name=\"LB\">{{Cite book|last=Schwarz |first=Richard W. |title=Light Bearers to the Remnant |year=1979 |publisher=Pacific Press |location=Boise, Idaho / Oshawa, Ontario, Canada}}</ref>\n* In 1931 a list of 22 Fundamental Beliefs<ref>[http://www.greatcontroversy.org/gco/orc/fb1931.php/ Online Research Center: Fundamental Beliefs of Seventh-day Adventists, 1931<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301060307/http://www.greatcontroversy.org/gco/orc/fb1931.php/ |date=March 1, 2007 }}</ref> was produced and published in the Adventist ''Yearbook'', and subsequently in the Adventist ''Church Manual''.\n* In 1980, the ''27 Fundamentals'' were instituted by the denomination's [[General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|General Conference]]. [[Fritz Guy]] was the secretary of the original committee which produced the 27 Fundamentals. They were discussed and adopted at the 1980 [[General Conference Session]]. [[Ron Graybill]] wrote the [[preamble]].<ref name=\"Schofield\">{{Cite journal   | last = Scofield   | first = Michael   | title = How the 27 Fundamental Beliefs Came to Be   | journal = [[Adventist Today]]   | volume = 8   | issue = 3   | pages = 11   | publisher = Adventist Today Foundation   | location = [[Loma Linda, California|Loma Linda]], [[California|CA]]   | issn = 1079-5499   | date = May\u2013June 2000   | url = http://www.atoday.com/content/how-27-fundamental-beliefs-came-be   | accessdate = 2008-09-23 }}</ref> They are expanded upon in the book ''Seventh-day Adventists Believe: A Biblical Exposition of 27 Fundamental Doctrines''.<ref>[http://www.sdanet.org/atissue/books/27/index.htm Seventh-day Adventists Believe... FILE: index.htm<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> This elaboration does not constitute the \"official\" position of the church.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n* In 2005 another belief was inserted, fundamental belief number 11 \"Growing in Christ\", in response to the requests of Adventists in developing nations for a statement on [[spiritual warfare]]. It was voted in at the 2005 Adventist [[General Conference Session]] held in [[St. Louis, Missouri]], yielding the current total of 28.\n\n==Preamble==\nThe preamble to the 28 Fundamentals states that Adventists accept the [[Bible]] as their only creed, and that revision of the statements may be expected during the church General Conference Session:\n\n<blockquote>Seventh-day Adventists accept the Bible as their only creed and hold certain fundamental beliefs to be the teaching of the Holy Scriptures. These beliefs, as set forth here, constitute the church's understanding and expression of the teaching of Scripture. Revision of these statements may be expected at a [[General Conference Session]] when the church is led by the [[Holy Spirit]] to a fuller understanding of Bible truth or finds better language in which to express the teachings of God's Holy Word.\"<ref name=\"28F\">{{Cite web |title=Fundamental Beliefs |publisher=[[Seventh-day Adventist Church]] |url=http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/index.html |accessdate=2006-09-12 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060902013256/http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/index.html |archivedate=2 September 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Theological beliefs==\n<!-- COPYRIGHT NOTICE\n\t\nPlease do not cut-and-paste the text of the 28 Fundamental Beliefs straight into this article, as this is a copyright violation.\n\nRather, summarize their content, put it into your own words, quote reliable secondary commentary on the points, etc. See the sections \"Text\" under [[Wikipedia:Non-free content#Acceptable use]] and under the section \"Unacceptable use\"\n\n-->\n\n===Doctrines of God===\n\n1. Holy Scriptures\n:\"The Holy Scriptures are the [[Biblical infallibility|infallible]] revelation of [God's] will.\" Adventist theologians generally reject the \"verbal inspiration\" position on Scripture held by many conservative [[evangelical Christians]]. They believe instead that God inspired the thoughts of the biblical authors, and that the authors then expressed these thoughts in their own words.<ref>{{harvnb|General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|2005|pp=14\u201316}}</ref> This view is popularly known as \"thought inspiration\", and most Adventist members hold to that view. According to Ed Christian, former ''[[Journal of the Adventist Theological Society|JATS]]'' editor, \"few if any [[Adventist Theological Society|ATS]] members believe in verbal inerrancy\".<ref>[http://www.atoday.com/magazine/2001/11/adventist-theological-society-0 The Adventist Theological Society] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071225063148/http://www.atoday.com/magazine/2001/11/adventist-theological-society-0 |date=2007-12-25 }}, an interview of Ed Christian by John McLarty.</ref>\n\n:Adventists generally reject [[Higher criticism|higher critical]] approaches to Scripture. The 1986 statement ''Methods of Bible Study'', urges Adventist Bible students to avoid relying on the use of the presuppositions and the resultant deductions associated with the historical-critical method.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/other_documents/other_doc4.html |title=Methods of Bible Study|ref=harv}}</ref>\n\n2. Trinity\n:The Godhead (Trinity) consists of the Eternal Father, the Lord Jesus the Christ, and the Holy Spirit.<ref>{{cite book|editor-last=Knight|editor-first=George|title=Seventh-day Adventists Answer Questions on Doctrine (Annotated edition)|year=2003|publisher=Andrews University Press|location=Berrien Springs, Michigan|ref=harv|page=5}}</ref>\n\n3. Father\n:God, the Eternal Father, is a personal and spiritual Being, who is omnipotent, omnipresent, omniscient. He is infinite in wisdom and love.<ref>{{harvnb|Knight|2003|p=5}}</ref>\n\n4. Son\n:Jesus, the Christ, is God in verity. He is of the same nature and essence as the Eternal Father. In addition, he took upon Himself human nature, living as a righteous man on earth, dying for the sins of mankind, raised from the dead and ascended to heaven where he makes intercession for mankind.<ref>{{harvnb|Knght|2003|p=5}}</ref>\n\n5. Holy Spirit\n:God the eternal Spirit was active with the Father and the Son in Creation, incarnation, and redemption. He is as much a person as are the Father and the Son. He inspired the writers of Scripture. He filled Christ\u2019s life with power. He draws and convicts human beings; and those who respond He renews and transforms into the image of God. Sent by the Father and the Son to be always with His children, He extends spiritual gifts to the church, empowers it to bear witness to Christ, and in harmony with the Scriptures leads it into all truth. ([[Genesis 1:1]], [[Genesis 1:2|2]]; 2 Samuel 23:2; Psalm 51:11; [[Isaiah 61:1]]; Luke 1:35; 4:18; John 14:16-18, 26; 15:26; 16:7-13; [[Acts 1:8]]; 5:3; 10:38; Romans 5:5; 1 Corinthians 12:7-11; 2 Corinthians 3:18; 2 Peter 1:21.)\n\n===The doctrines of humanity===\n\n6. Creation\n:The Seventh-day Adventist doctrine of creationism is based on believing that the opening chapters of Genesis should be interpreted as literal history. Adventist belief holds that all Earthly life originated during a six-day period some 6000 years ago, and a global flood destroyed all land based animals and humans except for those saved on Noah's Ark. Adventists oppose theories which propose interpreting the days of creation symbolically.<ref>{{harvnb|Numbers|2006|p=90}}</ref> \n\n:Although Adventists hold that creation week was a recent event, they believe the Bible speaks of other worlds populted by intelligent beings elsewhere in the universe, which pre-existed the Earth's creation week.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grisda.org/earth-antedated-by-other-created-worlds|title=Earth Antedated by Other Created Worlds, Ellen White Statements|last=White|first= Ellen|date=September 29, 2014|ref=harv}}</ref>  Instead of being ''The Word's'' first creation, the Earth was most likely His last one. The sons of God of Job 1:6-12 are the ''Adams'' of unfallen worlds meeting in God's presence somewhere in the universe. Other inhabited planets are located in the vastness of space\u2014well beyond the reach of space probes from our sin-polluted solar system, quarantined due to the infection of sin.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.grisda.org/earth-antedated-by-other-created-worlds|title=Earth Antedated by Other Created Worlds, Ellen White Statements|last=White|first= Ellen|date=September 29, 2014|ref=harv}}</ref> \n\n:Adventists believe that inorganic matter was created prior to the creation week and was altered into its present form during the creation week. Therefore, the computed radiometric dates of standard geology are irrelevant to dating the creation of life on Earth.<ref name=\"C. L. Webster\">\n{{Cite journal|title=GENESIS AND TIME: What Radiometric Dating Tells Us|url=https://www.grisda.org/genesis-and-time-what-radiometric-dating-tells-us|author=C. L. Webster|publisher=[[Geoscience Research Institute]]}}\n</ref><ref>\n{{Cite journal|url=http://dialogue.adventist.org/articles/17_1_groot_e.htm|title=Genesis and the cosmos: A unified picture?|author=Mart de Groot|journal=Dialogue|ref=harv|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080516235413/http://dialogue.adventist.org/articles/17_1_groot_e.htm|archive-date=2008-05-16|url-status=dead}}\n</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|url=http://www.atsjats.org/publication_file.php?pub_id=54&journal=1&type=pdf|title=The Creation Account in Genesis 1: Our World Only or the Universe?|author=Ferdinand O. Regalado|journal=Journal of the Adventist Theological Society 13/2:108-120|ref=harv|access-date=2018-02-09|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180223132402/http://www.atsjats.org/publication_file.php?pub_id=54&journal=1&type=pdf|archive-date=2018-02-23|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>\n{{Cite conference|url=http://christintheclassroom.org/vol_31B/31Bcc_159-181.htm|title=The Bible and Astronomy|author=Mart de Groot|publisher=Education Department, General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|access-date=2019-09-10|ref=harv}}\n</ref> Since radiometric dating, says Webster, is an \"interpretive science\", he believes that for the Christian scientist \u201cit would seem logical, almost compelling, to seriously consider\u201d the Biblical account \u201cfor determining the time of Creation.\"<ref name=\"C. L. Webster\" />\n\n7. Nature of Humanity\n\n===The doctrines of salvation===\n\n8. [[Great Controversy theme|The Great Controversy]]\n\n9. The Life, Death, and Resurrection of Christ\n\n10. The Experience of Salvation\n\n11. Growing in Christ\n\n===The doctrines of the church===\n\n12. The Church\n\n13. The Remnant and Its Mission\n\n14. Unity in the Body of Christ\n\n15. Baptism\n\n16. The Lord's Supper\n\n17. Spiritual Gifts and Ministries\n\n18. The Gift of Prophecy\n\n===The doctrines of Christian living===\n\n19. The Law of God\n\n20. The Sabbath\n\n21. Stewardship\n\n22. Christian Behavior\n\n23. Marriage and the Family\n\n===The doctrines of the restoration===\n\n24. Christ's Ministry in the Heavenly Sanctuary\n\n25. The Second Coming of Christ\n\n26. Death and Resurrection\n\n27. The Millennium and the End of Sin\n\n28. The New Earth\n\n==Shared Protestant doctrine==\n{{Non-free|section|small=left|date=December 2017}}\n{{Prose|section|small=left|date=December 2017}}\nIn ''[[Seventh-day Adventists Answer Questions on Doctrine]]'' (1957), the editors outlined the doctrines that they share with Protestant Christianity.\n\n:\"'''In Common With Conservative Christians and the Historic Protestant Creeds, We Believe\u2014'''\n\n:1. That God is the Sovereign Creator, upholder, and ruler of the universe, and that He is eternal, omnipotent, omniscient, and omnipresent.\n:2. That the Godhead, the [[Trinity]], comprises God the Father, Christ the Son, and the Holy Spirit.\n:3. That the Scriptures are the inspired revelation of God to men; and that the Bible is the sole rule of faith and practice.\n:4. That Jesus Christ is very God, and that He has existed with the Father from all eternity.\n:5. That the Holy Spirit is a personal being, sharing the attributes of deity with the Father and the Son.\n:6. That Christ, the Word of God, became [[incarnation (Christianity)|incarnate]] through the miraculous conception and the [[Virgin birth of Jesus|virgin birth]]; and that He lived an absolutely sinless life here on earth.\n:7. That the [[substitutionary atonement|vicarious, atoning death]] of Jesus Christ, once for all, is all-sufficient for the redemption of a lost race.\n:8. That Jesus Christ arose literally and bodily from the grave.\n:9. That He ascended literally and bodily into heaven.\n:10. That He now serves as our advocate in priestly ministry and mediation before the Father.\n:11. That He will return in a premillennial, personal, imminent second advent.\n:12. That man was [[creation myth|created]] sinless, but by his subsequent fall entered a state of alienation and depravity.\n:13. That salvation through Christ is by grace alone, through faith in His blood.\n:14. That entrance upon the new life in Christ is by regeneration, or the new birth.\n:15. That man is [[justification (theology)|justified by faith]].\n:16. That man is sanctified by the indwelling Christ through the Holy Spirit.\n:17. That man will be glorified at the [[resurrection of the dead|resurrection or translation of the saints]], when the [[second coming|Lord returns]].\n:18. That there will be a [[last judgment|judgment of all men]].\n:19. That the gospel is to be preached as a witness to all the world.\"<ref name=\"qod_chapt1\">[http://www.sdanet.org/atissue/books/qod/index.htm Seventh-day Adventists Answer Questions on Doctrine], Review and Herald Publishing Association, Washington D.C., 1957. Chapter 1 \"Doctrines We Share With Other Christians.\"</ref>\n\nAll of these doctrines, with the exception of item 11 (regarding the [[premillennialism|premillennial]] return of Christ), are widely held amongst conservative or [[evangelicalism|evangelical]] Protestants. (Different Protestant groups hold varying views on the millennium.)\n\nRegarding salvation, a major statement was the 1980 \"The Dynamics of Salvation\".<ref>[http://www.adventistbiblicalresearch.org/documents/Dynamics%20of%20Salvation.htm Adventistbiblicalresearch.org] ''Adventist Review'', July 31, 1980</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Christianity}}\t\n* [[History of the Seventh-day Adventist Church]]\n* [[The Pillars of Adventism]]\n* [[Seventh-day Adventist theology]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n* {{cite book|title=Seventh-day Adventists Believe|first=Ministerial Association|last=General Conference of Seventh-day Adventists|year=2005|publisher=Pacific Press Publishing Association|edition=2nd|ref=harv}}\n\n==External links==\n:''See also [[Seventh-day Adventist theology#External links]]''\n* [http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/fundamental/  Fundamental Beliefs] from the church's official website (see also [http://www.adventist.org/beliefs/statements/  Official Statements])\n* \"[http://www.sdanet.org/atissue/doctrines/au2002conference/guy/guy27origin.htm Uncovering the Origins of the Statement of Twenty-seven Fundamental Beliefs]\" by [[Fritz Guy]]. Presentation from the ''Being Adventist in 21st Century Australia'' Conference at [[Avondale College Church]], 2002.  Also ''[[Spectrum (magazine)|Spectrum]]'' v 32, Spring (2004), pp 18\u201329\n* \"[https://www.scribd.com/doc/8700702/seventhday-adventists-believe-1st-edition Seventh-Day Adventists Believe]\" ebook (1st ed)\n* A series of ''[[Adventist Review]]'' articles around 2008 described each doctrine. (also [https://web.archive.org/web/20090717123604/http://spectrummagazine.typepad.com/the_spectrum_blog/bloggin_the_28/  Blogging the 28], articles collated by ''Spectrum'')\n\nEach issue of ''Adventist World'' comments on a fundamental belief. Following is the list to February 2012 inclusive:<!-- only one issue from 2006, and April 2007 onwards available online; as of April 2009 --> [https://web.archive.org/web/20141014133943/http://www.adventistworld.org/article.php?id=859 1], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721212756/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2010-1002&page=22 2], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1003&page=20 3], [http://adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1003&page=20 5], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224602/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1002&page=20 6], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721212405/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1008&page=20 6], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224608/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1004&page=36 7], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224725/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1004&page=20 9], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1001&page=20 9], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224738/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1001&page=20 10], [https://web.archive.org/web/20091215051535/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1012&page=20 10], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721212518/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1004&page=20 11], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224743/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1007&page=20 12], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1011&page=20 12], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224751/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1009&page=20 15], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1007&page=20 15], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224800/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1005&page=20 16], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224808/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1012&page=12 16], [http://adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1007&page=20 17], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090220050428/http://adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1002&page=20 17], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2010-1001&page=20 17], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224849/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1011&page=20 19], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1006&page=22 20], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2010-1003&page=20 20], [https://web.archive.org/web/20090822204805/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2006-1008&page=20 21], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224908/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1006&page=20 21], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224914/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1011&page=12 22], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1010&page=20 22], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080509113357/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1005&page=22 23], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1009&page=20 23], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110721212216/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1008&page=20 24], [https://web.archive.org/web/20081014094635/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1010&page=22 24], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724224944/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1009&page=20 25], [https://web.archive.org/web/20110724225128/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1012&page=22 26], [http://adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2007-1010&page=20 27], [https://web.archive.org/web/20080803092414/http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2008-1008&page=20 27], [http://www.adventistworld.org/issue.php?issue=2009-1005&page=20 28]\n* ''Spectrum'' 8:4 (August 1977) [https://web.archive.org/web/20081202162437/http://spectrummagazine.org/spectrum/issue/vol_8_no_4_aug_1977 Special Section: An Adventist Creed?]\n* \"[http://docs.adventistarchives.org/docs/RH/RH19840712-V161-28__B.pdf  Why Seventh-day Adventists have no creed]\" (DjVu) by [[Arthur L. White]]. ''Adventist Review'' 161:28 (12 July 1984), pp 6\u20138\n* \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20080821132246/http://spectrummagazine.org/files/archive/archive11-15/11-1report.pdf  General Conference Report]\" section, by Lawrence Geraty and other authors. ''Spectrum'' 11:1 (July 1980)  ([https://web.archive.org/web/20090611025007/http://www.spectrummagazine.org/blog/2009/06/07/new_statement_fundamental_beliefs reprint] of Geraty article)\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080829163338/http://www.spectrummagazine.org/files/archive/archive11-15/11-3responses.pdf Letters to the editor] in ''Spectrum'' 11:3 (February 1981), pp 61\u2014\n* \"Creeds and Statements of Belief in Early Adventist Thought\" by S. Joseph Kidder. ''[[Andrews University Seminary Studies]]'' 47:1 (Spring 2009), pp 101\u201316\n* [http://jewel.andrews.edu:82/search/dCreeds Search for \"Creeds\"]{{Dead link|date=September 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} in the Seventh-day Adventist Periodical Index (SDAPI)\n\n[[Category:Seventh-day Adventist theology|Fundamentals, 28]]\n[[Category:Christian statements of faith]]\n[[Category:1980 in Christianity]]\n[[Category:1980 documents]]\n[[Category:20th-century Christian texts]]\n", "name_user": "Can I Log In", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fixing bad spacing with reference footnotes (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/28_Fundamental_Beliefs"}
{"title_page": "Christian Brembeck", "text_new": "[[File:Portrait Brembeck.jpg|thumb|Christian Brembeck, 2011]]\n'''Christian Brembeck''' (born 1960 in Munich) is a German conductor, organist and harpsichordist.\n\nHe studied organ, piano and conducting at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Theater M\u00fcnchen]] in Munich, and was awarded the Organ Prize of the City of [[W\u00fcrzburg]] in 1981. After graduating in 1987, he joined the [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]]. He has performed as a musician and conductor all over Europe, USA, Israel, the Far East and South America. He has also appeared with the [[Munich Radio Orchestra]], the [[Bamberger Symphoniker]] and the [[Collegium Aureum]]. He has been an accompanist of the [[T\u00f6lzer Knabenchor]]. Since 1992 he has been the conductor of the chamber orchestra [[Capella Istropolitana]] in [[Bratislava]].<ref>[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Brembeck-Christian.htm Christian Brembeck (Conductor, Organ, Harpsichord)] bach-cantatas.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB portal|131714325}}\n*[http://brembeck.net/ Christian Brembeck] website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120406212601/http://www.bravomaestro.com/module-mCatalog-view_executor-id_executor-33.phtml Brembeck, Organo] bravomaestro.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brembeck, Christian}}\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:German harpsichordists]]\n[[Category:Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Theater M\u00fcnchen alumni]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century organists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n\n\n{{Germany-conductor-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Portrait Brembeck.jpg|thumb|Christian Brembeck, 2011]]\n'''Christian Brembeck''' (born 1960 in Munich) is a German conductor, organist and harpsichordist.\n\nHe studied organ, piano and conducting at the [[Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Theater M\u00fcnchen]] in Munich, and was awarded the Organ Prize of the City of [[W\u00fcrzburg]] in 1981. After graduating in 1987, he joined the [[Munich Philharmonic Orchestra]]. He has performed as a musician and conductor all over Europe, USA, Israel, the Far East and South America. He has also appeared with the [[Munich Radio Orchestra]], the [[Bamberger Symphoniker]] and the [[Collgium Aureum]]. He has been an accompanist of the [[T\u00f6lzer Knabenchor]]. Since 1992 he has been the conductor of the chamber orchestra [[Capella Istropolitana]] in [[Bratislava]].<ref>[http://www.bach-cantatas.com/Bio/Brembeck-Christian.htm Christian Brembeck (Conductor, Organ, Harpsichord)] bach-cantatas.com</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{DNB portal|131714325}}\n*[http://brembeck.net/ Christian Brembeck] website\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20120406212601/http://www.bravomaestro.com/module-mCatalog-view_executor-id_executor-33.phtml Brembeck, Organo] bravomaestro.com\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brembeck, Christian}}\n[[Category:German conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German male conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:German organists]]\n[[Category:Male organists]]\n[[Category:German harpsichordists]]\n[[Category:Hochschule f\u00fcr Musik und Theater M\u00fcnchen alumni]]\n[[Category:1960 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:21st-century conductors (music)]]\n[[Category:21st-century organists]]\n[[Category:21st-century German male musicians]]\n\n\n{{Germany-conductor-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Bellowhead678", "label": "safe", "comment": "Collgium->Collegium -Fix a typo in one click", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Brembeck"}
{"title_page": "Struthiola striata", "text_new": "{{Short description|A shrub in the Thymelaeaceae family from South Africa}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Struthiola striata RF.jpg\n|genus = Struthiola\n|species = striata\n|authority = [[Lam.]]\n|synonyms =\n* ''S. striata'' var. ''angustifolia''\n* ''S. imbricata''\n* ''S. sulcata''\n* ''S. lateriflora''\n}}\n\n'''''Struthiola striata''''' is a rounded, heather-like shrub of up to {{cvt|1.5|m|ft}} high that is assigned to the [[Thymelaeaceae]] family. It has small assending leaves on long straight branches, with cream, soft yellow or pinkish flowers in spikes, each of which consist of a tube of about {{cvt|1|cm|in}} long with 4 oval sepal lobes and 4 yellow alternating petal-like scales.<ref name=MBMM>{{cite journal|first1= Thuli|last1= Makhoba|first2= James|last2= Boatwright|first3= John C.|last3= Manning|first4= Anthony Richard|last4= Magee|year= 2019|title= Taxonomy of the four-scaled species of Struthiola L. (Thymelaeaceae)|journal= South African Journal of Botany|volume= 121|pages= 577-583|doi= 10.1016/j.sajb.2019.01.031|url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/331446928_Taxonomy_of_the_four-scaled_species_of_Struthiola_L_Thymelaeaceae}}</ref> It is somtimes called '''featherhead''' in English<ref>{{cite web|title= Struthiola striata|website= Fernkloof Nature Reserve|url= https://www.fernkloof.org.za/index.php/all-plants/plant-families/item/struthiola-striata}}</ref> and '''roemenaggie''', '''katstertjie''' or '''ve\u00ebrtjie''' in [[Afrikaans]]. It grows on coastal flats and foot hills in the Western Cape province of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|author= Thuli Makhoba|title= Struthiola striata|website= PlantsZAfrica|publisher= SA National Biodiversity Institute|url= http://pza.sanbi.org/struthiola-striata}}</ref><ref name=PGCFR>{{cite book|first1= John|last1= Manning|first2= Peter|last2= Goldblatt|year= 2013|title= Plants of the Greater Cape Floristic Region - 1: The Core Cape Flora|pages= 777|series= Strelitzia|volume= 29|publisher= [[South African National Biodiversity Institute]]|url= https://www.sanbi.org/sites/default/files/documents/documents/strelitzia-29-2012.pdf}}</ref> \n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThis species was first described as ''Struthiola striata'' by [[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck]] in 1792, based on a collection by the French [[List of gardener-botanist explorers of the Enlightenment|gardener-botanist]] [[Joseph Martin (gardener)|Joseph Martin]] in the Cape area (Cap B. Spei). Later botanists however, overlooked this name. [[Franz Wilibald Schmidt]] named the species ''S. sulcata'' in 1793, [[Henry Cranke Andrews]] in 1800 created the name ''S. imbricata'', while [[Jens Wilken Hornemann]] assigned the name ''S. lateriflora'' to it in 1815. In 1843 [[Carl Daniel Friedrich Meissner|Meissner]] distinguished two varieties, ''S. striata'' var. ''striata'' and ''S. striata''  var. ''angustifolia''. In 1857 he considered ''S. sulcata'', ''S. imbricata'' and ''S. lateriflora'' [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonyms]] of ''S. striata''. [[Charles Henry Wright]] in 1915 in turn regarded ''S. striata'' var. ''angustifolia'' a synonym of ''S. striata''.<ref name=MBMM />\n\n== Description ==\n[[Image:Struthiola_striata_Berkel_1.jpg|thumb|Sideview of the flower]]Roemenaggie is a rounded shrub of up to {{cvt|1.5|m|ft}} high that emerges from a single trunk from the ground. The branches are initially covered in soft hairs pressed firmly to the surface, but become hairless when aging.\nThe leaves are [[Leaf#Arrangement on the stem|in pairs opposing each other]], more or less upright, overlapping each other, with the blade directly attached to the branche without a leaf stalk. They are oval to lance-shaped, {{cvt|5\u20138.5|mm|in}} long and generally {{cvt|2\u20134|mm|in}} wide, somewhat depressed along the main vein, almost pointed, with a row of hairs pressed to the surface along its rim. When the leaves are young 3 to 5 stripes are visible along the length of the outward facing surface.<ref name=MBMM />\n\nThe flowers are seated in the axils of the leaves over a considerable length towards the tip of the branches, an inflorescence type called a [[Raceme#Spike|spike]]. The two [[Bract#Bracteole|bracteoles]] are set opposite each other at the base of the flower, awl-shaped, about {{cvt|2.5|mm|in}} long, with a regular row of hairs along the margin and a blunt tip ending in a tuft of hairs. The [[Sepal|calyx]] is cream-coloured, with at its base a cylindrical tube of about {{cvt|1|cm|in}} long that is covered on the outside with soft hairs pressed against its surface and at its top 4 oval protracted, almost pointy lobes of {{cvt|1\u20132|mm|in}} long and {{cvt|1.5\u20132.5|mm|in}} wide, hairless but for a tuft of hairs at the tips. Four yellow, elliptic, petal-like scales are implanted above and alternating with the sepal lobes, and are surrounded by stiff hairs that may be shorter or longer than the scales. About {{cvt|1|mm|in}} below the mouth of the tube sits on whorl of four seated stamens 4, that have a reddish wart at their tips. The [[Ovary (botany)|ovary]] is egg-shaped, hairless and about 1 mm long, and is topped by a [[Stigma_(botany)#Style|style]] of about {{cvt|8|mm|in}} long and ends in a brush-like [[Stigma (botany)|stigma]].<ref name=MBMM />\n\n=== Differences with related species ===\n''Struthiola'' has its flowers arranged in long spikes, whereas ''[[Gnidia]]'' differs from it in having its flowers in short spikes, solitary or more often in heads. Both ''[[Lachnaea]]'', ''[[Passerina]]'' and a few ''Gnidia''-species lack scales on the calyx tubes. Both ''S. striata'' and ''S. tetralepis'' have four petal-like scales implanted at the opening of the calyx tube, while the many dozens of remaining ''Struthiola'' species have eight or twelve scales. ''S. striata'' is a roundish shrub of up to 1.5 m high with cream, soft yellow or pinkish flowers ending in oval sepal lobes of 1\u20132 mm long and 1.5\u20132.5 mm wide, and a reddish wart on the tip of the anthers, ''S. tetralepis'' is a single stemmed shrublet of up to {{cvt|30|cm|ft}} high that has initially greenish yellow, later brownish red flowers with lance-shaped sepal lobes of {{cvt|2\u20133|mm|in}} long and {{cvt|0.5\u20131.0|mm|in}} wide, and a white wart on the anthers.<ref name=FGtF>{{cite book|first= John|last= Manning|year= 2007|title= Field Guide to Fynbos|publisher= Random House Struik|location= Cape Town|pages= 236-245}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution, ecology and conservation == \n''Struthiola striata'' is restricted to coast of the Western Cape province of South Africa, between [[Yzerfontein]] in the north and [[Mossel Bay]] in the east. It occurs in a vegetation type called sand fynbos where it grows \non lower slopes and coastal sand flats.<ref name=MBMM /> It is honey-scented at night and gets pollinated by moths.<ref>{{cite journal|first1= Thuli|last1= Makhoba|first2= John C.|last2= Manning|year= 2006|title= First report of moth pollination in Struthiola ciliata (Thymelaeaceae) in southern Africa|journal= South African Journal of Botany|volume= 72|pages= 597\u2013603}}</ref> The continued survival of this species is considered to be of [[Least-concern species|least concern]] because its populations are stable.<ref>{{cite web|last1= Foden|first1= W.|last2= Potter|first2= L.|year= 2005|title= Struthiola striata Lam.|website= National Assessment: Red List of South African Plants version 2017|url= http://redlist.sanbi.org/species.php?species=2930-41}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from= }}\n\n[[Category:Thymelaeaceae|Struthiola striata]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|A shrub in the Thymelaeaceae family from South Africa}}\n{{Speciesbox\n|image = Struthiola striata RF.jpg\n|genus = Struthiola\n|species = striata\n|authority = [[Lam.]]\n|synonyms =\n* ''S. striata'' var. ''angustifolia''\n* ''S. imbricata''\n* ''S. sulcata''\n* ''S. lateriflora''\n}}\n\n'''''Struthiola striata''''' is a rounded, heather-like shrub of up to {{cvt|1.5|m|ft}} high that is assigned to the [[Thymelaeaceae]] family. It has small assending leaves on long straight branches, with cream, soft yellow or pinkish flowers in spikes, each of which consist of a tube of about {{cvt|1|cm|in}} long with 4 oval sepal lobes and 4 yellow alternating petal-like scales.<ref name=MBMM>{{cite journal|first1= Thuli|last1= Makhoba|first2= James|last2= Boatwright|first3= John C.|last3= Manning|first4= Anthony Richard|last4= Magee|year= 2019|title= Taxonomy of the four-scaled species of Struthiola L. (Thymelaeaceae)|journal= South African Journal of Botany|volume= 121|pages= 577-583|doi= 10.1016/j.sajb.2019.01.031|url= https://www.researchgate.net/publication/331446928_Taxonomy_of_the_four-scaled_species_of_Struthiola_L_Thymelaeaceae}}</ref> It is somtimes called '''featherhead''' in English<ref>{{cite web|title= Struthiola striata|website= Fernkloof Nature Reserve|url= https://www.fernkloof.org.za/index.php/all-plants/plant-families/item/struthiola-striata}}</ref> and '''roemenaggie''', '''katstertjie''' or '''ve\u00ebrtjie''' in [[Afrikaans]]. It grows on coastal flats and foot hills in the Western Cape province of South Africa.<ref>{{cite web|author= Thuli Makhoba|title= Struthiola striata|website= PlantsZAfrica|publisher= SA National Biodiversity Institute|url= http://pza.sanbi.org/struthiola-striata}}</ref><ref name=PGCFR>{{cite book|first1= John|last1= Manning|first2= Peter|last2= Goldblatt|year= 2013|title= Plants of the Greater Cape Floristic Region - 1: The Core Cape Flora|pages= 777|series= Strelitzia|volume= 29|publisher= [[South African National Biodiversity Institute]]|url= https://www.sanbi.org/sites/default/files/documents/documents/strelitzia-29-2012.pdf}}</ref> \n\n== Taxonomy ==\nThis species was first described as ''Struthiola striata'' by [[Jean-Baptiste Lamarck]] in 1792, based on a collection by the French [[List of gardener-botanist explorers of the Enlightenment|gardener-botanist]] [[Joseph Martin (gardener)|Joseph Martin]] in the Cape area (Cap B. Spei). Later botanists however, overlooked this name. [[Franz Wilibald Schmidt]] named the species ''S. sulcata'' in 1793, [[Henry Cranke Andrews]] in 1800 created the name ''S. imbricata'', while [[Jens Wilken Hornemann]] assigned the name ''S. lateriflora'' to it in 1815. In 1843 [[Carl Daniel Friedrich Meissner|Meissner]] distinguished two varieties, ''S. striata'' var. ''striata'' and ''S. striata''  var. ''angustifolia''. In 1857 he considered ''S. sulcata'', ''S. imbricata'' and ''S. lateriflora'' [[synonym (taxonomy)|synonyms]] of ''S. striata''. [[Charles Henry Wright]] in 1915 in turn regarded ''S. striata'' var. ''angustifolia'' a synonym of ''S. striata''.<ref name=MBMM />\n\n== Description ==\n[[Image:Struthiola_striata_Berkel_1.jpg|thumb|Sideview of the flower]]Roemenaggie is a rounded shrub of up to {{cvt|1.5|m|ft}} high that emerges from a single trunk from the ground. The branches are initially covered in soft hairs pressed firmly to the surface, but become hairless when aging.\nThe leaves are [[Leaf#Arrangement on the stem|in pairs opposing each other]], more or less upright, overlapping each other, with the blade directly attached to the branche without a leaf stalk. They are oval to lance-shaped, {{cvt|5\u20138.5|mm|in}} long and generally {{cvt|2\u20134|mm|in}} wide, somewhat depressed along the main vein, almost pointed, with a row of hairs pressed to the surface along its rim. When the leaves are young 3 to 5 stripes are visible along the length of the outward facing surface.<ref name=MBMM />\n\nThe flowers are seated in the axils of the leaves over a considerable length towards the tip of the branches, an inflorescence type called a [[Raceme#Spike|spike]]. The two [[Bract#Bracteole|bracteoles]] are set opposite each other at the base of the flower, awl-shaped, about {{cvt|2.5|mm|in}} long, with a regular row of hairs along the margin and a blunt tip ending in a tuft of hairs. The [[Sepal|calyx]] is cream-coloured, with at its base a cylindrical tube of about {{cvt|1|cm|in}} long that is covered on the outside with soft hairs pressed against its surface and at its top 4 oval protracted, almost pointy lobes of {{cvt|1\u20132|mm|in}} long and {{cvt|1.5\u20132.5|mm|in}} wide, hairless but for a tuft of hairs at the tips. Four yellow, elliptic, petal-like scales are implanted above and alternating with the sepal lobes, and are surrounded by stiff hairs that may be shorter or longer than the scales. About {{cvt|1|mm|in}} below the mouth of the tube sits on whorl of four seated stamens 4, that have a reddish wart at their tips. The [[Ovary (botany)|ovary]] is egg-shaped, hairless and about 1 mm long, and is topped by a [[Stigma_(botany)#Style|style]] of about {{cvt|8|mm|in}} long and ends in a brush-like [[Stigma (botany)|stigma]].<ref name=MBMM />\n\n=== Differences with related species ===\n''Struthiola'' has its flowers arranged in long spikes, whereas ''[[Gnidia]]'' differs from it in having its flowers in short spikes, solitary or more often in heads. Both ''[[Lachnaea]]'', ''[[Passerina]]'' and a few ''Gnidia''-species lack scales on the calyx tubes. Both ''S. striata'' and ''S. tetralepis'' have four petal-like scales implanted at the opening of the calyx tube, while the many dozens of remaining ''Struthiola'' species have eight or twelve scales. ''S. striata'' is roundish shrub of up to 1.5 m high with cream, soft yellow or pinkish flowers ending in oval sepal lobes of 1\u20132 mm long and 1.5\u20132.5 mm wide, and a reddish wart on the tip of the anthers, ''S. tetralepis'' is a single stemmed shrublet of up to {{cvt|30|cm|ft}} high that has initially greenish yellow, later brownish red flowers with lance-shaped sepal lobes of {{cvt|2\u20133|mm|in}} long and {{cvt|0.5\u20131.0|mm|in}} wide, and a white wart on the anthers.<ref name=FGtF>{{cite book|first= John|last= Manning|year= 2007|title= Field Guide to Fynbos|publisher= Random House Struik|location= Cape Town|pages= 236-245}}</ref>\n\n== Distribution, ecology and conservation == \n''Struthiola striata'' is restricted to coast of the Western Cape province of South Africa, between [[Yzerfontein]] in the north and [[Mossel Bay]] in the east. It occurs in a vegetation type called sand fynbos where it grows \non lower slopes and coastal sand flats.<ref name=MBMM /> It is honey-scented at night and gets pollinated by moths.<ref>{{cite journal|first1= Thuli|last1= Makhoba|first2= John C.|last2= Manning|year= 2006|title= First report of moth pollination in Struthiola ciliata (Thymelaeaceae) in southern Africa|journal= South African Journal of Botany|volume= 72|pages= 597\u2013603}}</ref> The continued survival of this species is considered to be of [[Least-concern species|least concern]] because its populations are stable.<ref>{{cite web|last1= Foden|first1= W.|last2= Potter|first2= L.|year= 2005|title= Struthiola striata Lam.|website= National Assessment: Red List of South African Plants version 2017|url= http://redlist.sanbi.org/species.php?species=2930-41}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Taxonbar|from= }}\n\n[[Category:Thymelaeaceae|Struthiola striata]]\n", "name_user": "Dwergenpaartje", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDifferences with related species", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Struthiola_striata"}
{"title_page": "Investigatory Powers Act 2016", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Investigatory Powers Act 2016\n|type                 = Act\n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom\n|long_title           =\n|year                 = 2016\n|citation             =\n|introduced_by        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Theresa May]], <small>as [[Home Secretary]]</small>\n* [[Frederick Curzon, 7th Earl Howe|The Earl Howe]], <small>as [[Leader of the House of Lords|Dep. Ldr (Lords)]]</small>}}\n|territorial_extent   = [[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]] and [[Northern Ireland]]<!-- [[British overseas territories]] is extended by the [[Privy Council]] under s.233(6) -->\n|amends               = {{startplainlist}}\n* [[Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000]]\n* [[Terrorism Act 2006]]\n* [[Wireless Telegraphy Act 2006]]\n* [[Serious Crime Act 2007]]\n* [[Counter-Terrorism Act 2008]]\n* [[Policing and Crime Act 2009]]\n* [[Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures Act 2011]]\n* [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]]\n* [[Data Retention and Investigatory Powers Act 2014]]\n* [[Counter-Terrorism and Security Act 2015]]\n* [[Serious Crime Act 2015]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n|royal_assent         = 2nd July 2016\n|commencement         =\n|repeal_date          =\n|replaces             =\n|amendments           =\n|related_legislation  =\n|repealing_legislation=\n|status               = Current\n|original_text        =\n|legislation_history  =\n|use_new_UK-LEG       = yes\n|UK-LEG_title         =\n|revised_text         =\n|theyworkforyou       =\n|millbankhansard      =\n}}\nThe '''Investigatory Powers Act 2016''' (nicknamed the '''Snoopers' Charter''')<ref>{{cite web|last1=Griffin|first1=Andrew|title=UK spying laws: Government introduces law requiring WhatsApp and iMessage to break their own security|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/uk-spying-laws-uk-government-introduces-law-requiring-whatsapp-and-imessage-to-be-broken-a6905106.html|website=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=1 March 2016}}</ref> is an Act of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] that has been passed by both Houses of Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/news/450403089/Investigatory-Powers-Bill-looks-set-to-become-law|title=Investigatory Powers Bill looks set to become law|author=Warwick Ashford|date=17 November 2016|work=computerweekly.com|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Queen Elizabeth II]] signified her [[Royal assent#United Kingdom|royal assent]] to the Investigatory Powers Act 2016 on 2nd July 2016.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/19/extreme-surveillance-becomes-uk-law-with-barely-a-whimper 'Extreme surveillance' becomes UK law with barely a whimper] Published by [[The Guardian]], 19 November 2016, accessed on the same day</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=editor|first1=Alan Travis Home affairs|title='Snooper's charter' bill becomes law, extending UK state surveillance|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/29/snoopers-charter-bill-becomes-law-extending-uk-state-surveillance|website=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2016|date=29 November 2016}}</ref> Its different parts come into force on various dates from 30 December 2016.<ref name=\":3\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-act-bill-snoopers-charter-spying-law-powers-theresa-may-a7503616.html Investigatory Powers Act goes into force, putting UK citizens under intense new spying regime] Published by The Independent, 31 December 2016</ref> The Act comprehensively sets out and in limited respects expands the electronic surveillance powers of the [[UK intelligence community|UK Intelligence Community]] and police.<ref name=\":3\"/> It also aims to improve the safeguards on the exercise of those powers.<ref name=\"Guardian 27-4-2018\">{{Cite web |last=Cobain |first=Ian |title=UK has six months to rewrite snooper's charter, high court rules |website=The Guardian |language=en |date=27 April 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/27/snoopers-charter-investigatory-powers-act-rewrite-high-court-rules |access-date=2018-06-19}}</ref>\n\n== Drafting and scrutiny ==\nIn 2014 the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK government]] asked [[David Anderson (barrister)|David Anderson]], the [[Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation]], to review the operation and regulation of investigatory powers available to law enforcement and intelligence agencies, in particular the interception of communications and communications data, and to recommend change. This report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daqc.co.uk/2015/06/11/a-question-of-trust-report-of-the-investigatory-powers-review/|title=A Question of Trust - Report of the Investigatory Powers Review (June 2015)|last=David Anderson|date=2015-06-11|website=David Anderson QC Lawyer London UK|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> was published in June 2015 and recommended a new law to clarify these powers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Surveillance powers: New law needed, says terror watchdog|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33092894|accessdate=8 June 2016|work=BBC|date=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Draft Investigatory Powers Bill was published in November 2015, with a large number of accompanying documents, and a [[Joint committee (legislative)|Joint Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and [[House of Lords]] was established to scrutinise the draft bill.<ref>{{cite web|title=Draft Bills 2015-16|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/bills-and-legislation/draft-bills/previous-sessions/draft-bills-2015-16/|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> Some parts of the bill referring to [[bulk personal datasets]] came into effect in November 2015, before parliamentary scrutiny began.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oral evidence: Draft Investigatory Powers Bill: Technology Issues HC573, Q.26 and Q.76|url=http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/science-and-technology-committee/investigatory-powers-bill-technology-issues/oral/24378.pdf|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref> The Joint Committee published its pre-legislative scrutiny report in March 2016. The Government accepted the vast majority of its 198 recommendations,<ref>{{cite web|title=Government publishes Investigatory Powers Bill|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/joint-select/draft-investigatory-powers-bill/news-parliament-2015/government-response-published/|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|date=2 March 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> together with the recommendations of two other parliamentary committees that had scrutinised the draft Bill, and the revised bill was introduced in the House of Commons,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill 2015-16 to 2016-17|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/investigatorypowers.html|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> where it was subject to debate by Members of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: Remaining Stages|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/investigatory-powers-bill-commons-second-reading/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016|date=7 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: Committee Stage Report|journal=House of Commons Library|date=2 June 2016|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7578|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7578|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 the House of Commons passed the Investigatory Powers Bill on its second reading by 281 votes to 15, moving the bill to the committee stage.<ref>Ryan Gallagher, [https://theintercept.com/2016/03/15/uk-parliament-debates-snoopers-charter/ U.K. Parliament Debates 'Snoopers' Charter], ''The Intercept (March 15, 2016).''</ref> The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[Scottish National Party]] abstained from the vote, while the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] voted against it.<ref>Kelly Fiveash, [http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/03/investigatory-powers-bill-labour-and-snp-to-abstain-from-parliamentary-vote/ MPs vote in favour of Investigatory Powers Bill after Labour, SNP abstain &#91;Updated&#93;], ''Ars Technica'' (15 March 2016).</ref><ref>Rowena Mason, Anushka Asthana & Alan Travis, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/15/delay-investigatory-powers-bill-scrutiny-mps-second-reading-firms-campaigners 'Snooper's charter': Theresa May faces calls to improve bill to protect privacy], ''The Guardian'' (15 March 2016).</ref>\n\nAt the committee stage constitutional,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill constitutional implications assessed by Committee|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/lords-select/constitution-committee/news-parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-report/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=19 November 2016|date=11 July 2016}}</ref> technology,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: technology issues inquiry|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-bill-technology-issues-inquiry-launch-15-16/|publisher=Science and Technology Committee (House of Commons)}}</ref> and human rights issues were examined. The Labour Chair of the [[Joint Committee on Human Rights]], [[Harriet Harman]], said:\n{{Quote|text=The Bill provides a clear and transparent basis for powers already in use by the security and intelligence services, but there need to be further safeguards. Protection for MP communications from unjustified interference is vital, as it is for confidential communications between lawyers and clients, and for journalists\u2019 sources, the Bill must provide tougher safeguards to ensure that the Government cannot abuse its powers to undermine Parliament\u2019s ability to hold the Government to account.|author= Harriet Harman|source=<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: direction of travel welcome, but improvements proposed|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/joint-select/human-rights-committee/news-parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-report-published-16-17/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=19 November 2016|date=2 June 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nAt this stage, at the insistence of the Labour Party, the [[Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation]] was commissioned to conduct a further review of the operational case for the bulk powers reserved under the Bill to the UK intelligence agencies: bulk interception, bulk collection of metadata, bulk equipment interference and the retention and use of bulk datasets. That review was conducted with the help of a small, security-cleared expert team, and together with 60 case studies, was published in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daqc.co.uk/2016/08/16/mass-surveillance-bulk-powers-review-august-2016/|title=Report of Bulk Powers Review, August 2016|last=David Anderson|date=2016-08-16|website=David Anderson QC Lawyer London UK|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> Like the 2014-15 reports of the [[Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board|PCLOB]]<ref>https://pclob.gov/library/215-Report_on_the_Telephone_Records_Program.pdf (s215); https://pclob.gov/library/702-Report-2.pdf (s702).</ref> and [[National Academy of Sciences]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.nap.edu/catalog/19414/bulk-collection-of-signals-intelligence-technical-options|title=Bulk Collection of Signals Intelligence: Technical Options|last=Council|first=National Research|date=2015-01-15|isbn=9780309325202|language=en|doi=10.17226/19414}}</ref> in the USA, it is a significant information source for the utility of so-called [[mass surveillance]] techniques\n\nOn 16 November 2016 the [[House of Lords]] approved the final version of the Investigatory Powers Bill, leaving only the formality of [[Royal Assent]] to be completed before the Bill became law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Act imminent as peers clear path for UK super-snoop law|url=http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/11/investigatory-powers-act-imminent-peers-clear-path-for-uk-super-snoop-law/|publisher=Ars Technica|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2016, the [[European Court of Justice]] (ECJ) declared that the generalised retention of certain types of personal data is unlawful, although little is known as to how this will affect the Investigatory Powers Act at this stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2016/dec/21/eus-highest-court-delivers-blow-to-uk-snoopers-charter|title=EU's highest court delivers blow to UK snooper's charter|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=2016-12-21|work=|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-12-21|via=}}</ref> As of 29 January 2017, many sources have since reported on the Investigatory Powers Act as if it is currently in action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Challenges-of-complying-with-the-Investigatory-Powers-Act|title=Challenges of complying with the Investigatory Powers Act|newspaper=ComputerWeekly|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-act-bill-snoopers-charter-spying-law-powers-theresa-may-a7503616.html|title=You just became subject to some of the most intense spying laws ever|date=2016-12-31|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nouse.co.uk/2017/01/29/nothing-to-hide-plenty-to-fear-from-prying-pm/|title=Nothing to hide, plenty to fear from prying PM|last=Bentley|first=Oscar|date=2017-01-29|website=Nouse|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=91acc531-5b9c-483b-bd8f-2fd27619244a|title=Investigatory Powers Act 2016: How to Prepare For A Digital Age {{!}} Lexology|last=K|last2=Braamskamp|first2=L. Gates-Christine|access-date=2017-01-29|last3=Gilchrist|first3=rew W.|last4=Millward|first4=James G.}}</ref> Draft codes of practice laid out by the Home Office in February 2017 did not provide insight on the Government's communications data code of practise, as it was for the Court of Appeal to decide how to apply the December ruling of the ECJ on data retention in member states.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/investigatory-powers-act-2016-codes-of-practice|title=Investigatory Powers Act 2016: codes of practice - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk}}</ref> It was then reported in late February 2017 that the aspects of the Bill forcing [[communications service provider]]s to retain data had been \"[[mothball#Verb|mothballed]]\" due to the ECJ ruling on the \"general and indiscriminate\" retention of communications data being illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/investigatory-powers-law-missing-draft-communications-data-code/|title=UK forced to derail Snoopers' Charter blanket data slurp after EU ruling|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Provisions of the Act ==\nThe Act:<ref name=BBC051115>{{cite news|title=UK surveillance powers explained|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34713435|accessdate=9 November 2015|work=BBC|date=5 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|title=Details of UK website visits 'to be stored for year'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34715872|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=BBC|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unveils powers to spy on web use, raising privacy fears|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/11/05/uk-britain-security-surveillance-idUKKCN0SS2RK20151105|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=Reuters|date=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Investigatory powers bill: the key points|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/04/investigatory-powers-bill-the-key-points|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|title=Surveillance Q&A: what web data is affected \u2013 and how to foil the snoopers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/04/surveillance-laws-theresa-may-snoopers-charter-internet-browsing-qa|accessdate=15 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* introduced new powers, and restated existing ones, for [[list of intelligence agencies of the United Kingdom|UK intelligence agencies]] and [[law enforcement in the United Kingdom|law enforcement]] to carry out targeted interception of [[telecommunication|communications]], bulk collection of [[communications data]], and bulk interception of communications;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Targeted Interception|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473739/Factsheet-Targeted_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Communications Data|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473755/Factsheet-Bulk_Communications_Data.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Interception|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473751/Factsheet-Bulk_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Communications Data|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473747/Factsheet-Communications_Data_General.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Personal Datasets|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473750/Factsheet-Bulk_Personal_Datasets.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473756/Factsheet-Bill_Definitions.pdf|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bill Definitions|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* created an Investigatory Powers Commission (IPC) to oversee the use of all investigatory powers, alongside the oversight provided by the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] and the [[Investigatory Powers Tribunal]]. The IPC consists of a number of serving or former senior judges. It combined and replaced the powers of the Interception of Communications Commissioner, Intelligence Services Commissioner, and Chief Surveillance Commissioner;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Oversight|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473741/Factsheet-Oversight.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=FactsheetIPC>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Investigatory Powers Commission|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473744/Factsheet-Investigatory_Powers_Commission.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* established a requirement for a judge serving on the IPC to review warrants for accessing the content of communications and equipment interference authorised by a Secretary of State before they come into force;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Authorisation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473758/Factsheet-Authorisation.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* required [[communication service providers]] (CSPs) to [[telecommunications data retention|retain]] UK internet users' \"Internet connection records\" \u2013 which websites were visited but not the particular pages and not the full browsing history \u2013 for one year;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473745/Factsheet-Internet_Connection_Records.pdf|title=Factsheet \u2013 Internet Connection Records|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* allowed police, intelligence officers and other government department managers (listed below) to see the Internet connection records, as part of a targeted and filtered investigation, without a warrant;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Request filter|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473748/Factsheet-CD_Request_Filter.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* permitted the police and intelligence agencies to carry out targeted equipment interference, that is, hacking into computers or devices to access their data,<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Targeted Equipment Interference|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473740/Factsheet-Targeted_Equipment_Interference.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> and bulk equipment interference for national security matters related to foreign investigations;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Equipment Interference|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473751/Factsheet-Bulk_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* placed a legal obligation on CSPs to assist with targeted interception of data, and communications and equipment interference in relation to an investigation; foreign companies are not required to engage in bulk collection of data or communications;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* maintained an existing requirement on CSPs in the UK to have the ability to remove encryption applied by the CSP; foreign companies are not required to remove encryption;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* put the [[Wilson Doctrine]] on a statutory footing for the first time as well as safeguards for other sensitive professions such as journalists, lawyers and doctors;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* provided local government with some investigatory powers, for example to investigate someone fraudulently claiming benefits, but not access to Internet connection records;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* created a new criminal offence for unlawfully accessing internet data;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* created a new criminal offence for a CSP or someone who works for a CSP to reveal that data has been requested.<ref name=BBC051115/>\n\n=== Investigatory Powers Commissioner ===\nThe Act created the role of Investigatory Powers Commissioner to provide independent oversight of the use of investigatory powers by intelligence agencies, police forces and other public authorities. In March 2017 Lord Justice Sir [[Adrian Fulford]], a Court of Appeal judge, was appointed as first Commissioner for a three-year term. His office (IPCO)<ref name=ipco>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipco.org.uk/ |title=Investigatory Powers Commissioner's Office |publisher=Investigatory Powers Commissioner's Office |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> will have fifteen senior judges as judicial commissioners, a technical advisory panel of scientific experts, and around 50 staff.<ref name=itv-20180616>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-16/who-is-the-investigatory-powers-commissioner-and-what-does-the-role-involve/ |title=Who is the Investigatory Powers Commissioner and what does the role involve? |work=ITV News |date=16 June 2018 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=gov-20170303>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/investigatory-powers-commissioner-appointed-lord-justice-fulford |title=Investigatory Powers Commissioner appointed: Lord Justice Fulford |publisher=gov.uk |date=3 March 2017 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 the [[Home Office]] blocked the appointment of Eric King as head of investigations at IPCO, citing national security grounds. King had previously been director of the Don\u2019t Spy On Us coalition, and deputy director of [[Privacy International]] for five years. King commented \"The problem, at its heart, is that there\u2019s a conflict as to whether my previous work and views are a positive or negative thing. They are both the reason I was hired and the reason my clearance was refused by the Home Office vetting team.\"<ref name=guardian-20190119>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/19/edward-snowden-defender-eric-king-vetoed-top-surveillance-watchdog-job |title=Home Office under fire for blocking new spy watchdog |last=Townsend |first=Mark |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 January 2019 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Authorities allowed to access Internet connection records ===\nList of authorities allowed to access Internet connection records without a warrant:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/bills/lbill/2016-2017/0040/17040.pdf|title=Investigatory Powers Bill \u2014 Schedule 4 \u2014 Relevant public authorities and designated senior officers|last=|first=|date=|website=www.parliament.uk|publisher=Parliament|page=212|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/ip-bill-law-details-passed|title=Snooper's Charter is set to become law: how the Investigatory Powers Bill will affect you|last=Burgess|first=Matt|newspaper=WIRED UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-bill-act-snoopers-charter-browsing-history-what-does-it-mean-a7436251.html|title=The list of organisations that will be allowed to view your entire internet history|date=2016-11-24|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref>\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Metropolitan Police Service]]\n* [[City of London Police]]\n* Police forces maintained under section 2 of the Police Act 1996\n* [[Police Scotland|Police Service of Scotland]]\n* [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]]\n* [[British Transport Police]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence Police]]\n* [[Royal Navy Police]]\n* [[Royal Military Police]]\n* [[Royal Air Force Police]]\n* [[MI5|Security Service]]\n* [[Secret Intelligence Service]]\n* [[Government Communications Headquarters|GCHQ]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence]]\n* [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]]\n* [[Home Office]]\n* [[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]]\n* [[National Crime Agency]]\n* [[HM Revenue and Customs|HM Revenue & Customs]]\n* [[Department for Transport]]\n* [[Department for Work and Pensions]]\n* NHS trusts and foundation trusts in England that provide ambulance services\n* [[Common Services Agency for the Scottish Health Service|NHS National Services Scotland]]\n* [[Competition and Markets Authority]]\n* [[Criminal Cases Review Commission]]\n* [[Department for Communities|Department for Communities (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Department for the Economy|Department for the Economy (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Department of Justice (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Financial Conduct Authority]]\n* Fire and rescue authorities under the Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004\n* [[Food Standards Agency]]\n* [[Food Standards Scotland]]\n* [[Gambling Commission]]\n* [[Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority]]\n* [[Health and Safety Executive]]\n* [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]]\n* [[Information Commissioner's Office|Information Commissioner]]\n* [[NHS Business Services Authority]]\n* [[Northern Ireland Ambulance Service|Northern Ireland Ambulance Service Health and Social Care Trust]]\n* [[Northern Ireland Fire and Rescue Service|Northern Ireland Fire and Rescue Service Board]]\n* [[Health & Social Care Business Services Organisation|Health & Social Care Business Services Organisation (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Ofcom|Office of Communications]]\n* [[Office of the Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland|Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland]]\n* [[Police Investigations and Review Commissioner]]\n* [[Scottish Ambulance Service Board]]\n* [[Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission]]\n* [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]]\n* [[Welsh Ambulance Service|Welsh Ambulance Services National Health Service Trust]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Public debate==\n{{Quote box\n|quote= Does the UK really want the dubious honor of introducing powers deemed too intrusive by all other major democracies, joining the likes of China and Russia in collecting everyone's browsing habits?<ref name = \"Bloomberg most spied\"/>\n|source= \u2014Anne Jellema, head of the [[World Wide Web Foundation]]\n|align= right\n|width = 42%\n|bgcolor= AliceBlue\n|quoted= yes\n|salign= right\n}}\nThe draft Bill generated significant public debate about balancing intrusive powers and [[mass surveillance]] with the needs of the police and intelligence agencies to gain targeted access to information as part of their investigations.<ref>{{cite web|title=May wrong to say surveillance bill creates judicial authorisation for interception, says Liberty \u2013 live|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2015/nov/04/surveillance-internet-snoopers-charter-may-plans-politics-live|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=11 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Will Europe call the shots?|url=https://terrorismlegislationreviewer.independent.gov.uk/will-europe-call-the-shots/|accessdate=11 November 2015|publisher=Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation|date=7 November 2015}}</ref> Although the [[Home Office]] said the Bill will be compatible with the [[European Convention on Human Rights]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill \u2013 European Convention on Human Rights Memorandum|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473763/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights_Memorandum.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> the content of the draft Bill has raised concerns about the impact on [[privacy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Guardian view on the draft investigatory powers bill: snooper's charter 3.0|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/02/the-guardian-view-on-the-draft-investigatory-powers-bill-snoopers-charter-30|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill - Privacy Impact Assessment|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473778/Privacy-Impact-Assessment.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nPrivacy campaigners say the bill clearly lays out the mass surveillance powers that would be at the disposal of the security services, and want it amended so that the surveillance is [[targeted surveillance|targeted]] and based on suspicion and argue that the powers are so sweeping, and the bill's language so general, that not just the security services but also government bodies will be able to analyse the records of millions of people even if they are not under suspicion.<ref name=ft1>{{cite web|last1=Vi\u00f1a|first1=Gonzalo|title=Surveillance: Taking liberties?|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1b7df076-57bb-11e6-9f70-badea1b336d4|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 a report published by the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] recommended that the bill should focus on the right to privacy. Committee chairman, Conservative MP [[Dominic Grieve]], said: \"We have therefore recommended that the new legislation contains an entirely new part dedicated to overarching privacy protections, which should form the backbone of the draft legislation around which the exceptional powers are then built. This will ensure that privacy is an integral part of the legislation rather than an add-on.\" The committee also recommended that Class bulk personal dataset warrants are removed from the legislation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Internet monitoring bill 'must do more to protect privacy'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35531721|date=9 February 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=9 February 2016}}</ref> Dominic Grieve later clarified the extent of these freedoms, \"the principle of the right to privacy against the state is maintained except if there is a good and sufficient reason why that should not happen.\"<ref>Third Reading of the Investigatory Powers Bill, Hansard, 6 June 2016.\n</ref>\n\nGavin E. L. Hall, a doctoral researcher at the [[University of Birmingham]], argues that public fear of the bill is not justified, writing that there are benefits to formally codifying in law what state security services can and cannot do and that \"While it may technically be possible under the bill to impugn individual freedom, [[John Bull]] has little to fear.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gavin E. L. Hall|title=Is the Snooper's Charter as Bad as You Think?|url=http://www.fairobserver.com/region/europe/is-the-snoopers-charter-as-bad-as-you-think-32300/|accessdate=11 March 2016|work=Fair Observer|date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Register]]'' argued the Act enshrines [[parallel construction]] in law and allows the state to lie about the origins of evidence in court, treating it as infallible, and prohibit the defendant from questioning it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/12/06/parallel_construction_lies_in_english_courts/|title=The UK's Investigatory Powers Act allows the State to tell lies in court|first=Gareth Corfield 6 Dec 2016|last=at 09:00|website=www.theregister.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n[[Article 19]], a freedom of expression campaign group, criticized the Act as one of the most draconian pieces of surveillance legislation passed worldwide, warning that it \"offers a template for authoritarian regimes and seriously undermining the rights of its citizens to privacy and freedom of expression\".<ref>The Guardian, \"Global press freedom plunges to worst level this century\", 30 November 2017 https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/nov/30/press-freedom-at-all-time-low-journalist-safety-article-19-v-dem-study</ref> The Chinese government cited the Snooper's Charter (officially the [[Draft Communications Data Bill]]) when defending its own intrusive anti-terrorism legislation.<ref name = \"Bloomberg most spied\">{{Cite web|title = 'Snooper's Charter' Would Make Brits Most Spied-Upon People|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-02-11/-snooper-s-charter-would-make-brits-most-spied-upon-people|website = Bloomberg|access-date = 11 February 2016|first = Kristen|last = Schweizer|date = 11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nRecent Wikileaks articles suggest that phone and digital device tracking both direct and indirect (eg FM radio blipping via Android exploit) also mentioned in Register posts by \"Anonymous Coward\" to covertly follow subjects have been used in the past but for operational reasons it is not clear if they are still used. The original poster has since decided to cooperate with the authorities and not comment further publicly on this subject, though the technique was independently rediscovered before the article in question was released.\n\n== Legal challenge and ruling ==\nIn November 2016, a petition demanding the law be repealed gained 100,000 signatures.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Titcomb|first1=James|title=Petition to repeal new surveillance powers reaches 100,000 signatures|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/11/28/petition-repeal-uks-new-surveillance-powers-reaches-100000-signatures/|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 March 2017|date=30 November 2016}}</ref> In December 2016, pornographic media site [[xHamster]] redirected UK traffic to the petition.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGoogan|first1=Cara|title=Porn website xHamster sends UK visitors to online petition against Snoopers' Charter|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/12/09/porn-website-xhamster-sends-uk-visitors-petition-against-snoopers/|newspaper=Telegraph|accessdate=9 March 2017|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> In March 2017, [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]], a human rights organisation, raised \u00a350,000 via crowd funding towards legal actions against the bill. Silkie Carlo, policy officer at Liberty, said: {{quote|The powers we're fighting undermine everything that's core to our freedom and democracy \u2014 our right to protest, to express ourselves freely and to a fair trial, our free press, privacy and cybersecurity. But with so much public support behind us, we're hopeful we will be able to persuade our courts to restrain the more authoritarian tendencies of this Government.|Silkie Carlo, policy officer at Liberty<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hopping|first1=Clare|title=Liberty launches legal challenge against Investigatory Powers Act|url=http://www.itpro.co.uk/it-legislation/28251/liberty-launches-legal-challenge-against-investigatory-powers-act|publisher=IT Pro|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 2018 the UK high court ruled that the Investigatory Powers Act violates EU law.<ref name=\"Guardian 27-4-2018\"/> The government had until 1 November 2018 to amend the legislation.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carey |first=Scott |title=The Snoopers' Charter: Everything you need to know about the Investigatory Powers Act |website=Computerworld UK |date=27 April 2018 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG UK]] |url=https://www.computerworlduk.com/security/draft-investigatory-powers-bill-what-you-need-know-3629116/ |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref> On 31 October 2018 The Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2018/1123/made/data.htm|title=The Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref> came into force to address this ruling. These regulations increased the threshold for accessing communications data only for the purposes of serious crime (defined as offences which are capable of being sentenced to imprisonment for a term of 12 months or more) and requires that authorities consult an independent Investigatory Powers Commissioner before requesting data. The regulations also included a loophole where rapid approval can be made internally without independent approval but with a three day expiry and with subsequent review by the independent body. Most debates about the regulations have been about the definition of \"serious crime\" with many arguing that the threshold should be at three years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2018-10-30a.1289.1|title=Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018 - Motion to Approve: 30 Oct 2018: House of Lords debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bill on Intelligence]] (French law)\n* [[Draft Communications Data Bill]], a draft bill produced for consultation in 2012 but never introduced to Parliament\n* ''{{lang|de|[[Gesetz zur Beschr\u00e4nkung des Brief-, Post- und Fernmeldegeheimnisses]]}}'' (German law)\n* [[Mass surveillance in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Patriot Act]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2016/25/contents/enacted Full text of the act as enacted] at [[legislation.gov.uk]]\n* {{cite web|title=Draft Investigatory Powers Bill|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/draft-investigatory-powers-bill|publisher=Home Office}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Draft Investigatory Powers Bill|journal=House of Commons Library|date=19 November 2015|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7371|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7371|accessdate=8 June 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Investigatory Powers Bill|journal=House of Commons Library|date=11 March 2016|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7518|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7518|accessdate=8 June 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Have your say on the Investigatory Powers Bill|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/have-your-say-on-the-investigatory-powers-bill/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016|date=16 March 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Surveillance]]\n[[Category:Government databases in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement techniques]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorism]]\n[[Category:Mass surveillance]]\n[[Category:National security policies]]\n[[Category:Surveillance databases]]\n[[Category:2015 in British law]]\n[[Category:Home Office (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Government Communications Headquarters]]\n[[Category:2015 in British politics]]\n[[Category:Data laws of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 2016]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=July 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK legislation\n|short_title          = Investigatory Powers Act 2016\n|type                 = Act\n|parliament           = Parliament of the United Kingdom\n|long_title           =\n|year                 = 2016\n|citation             =\n|introduced_by        = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Theresa May]], <small>as [[Home Secretary]]</small>\n* [[Frederick Curzon, 7th Earl Howe|The Earl Howe]], <small>as [[Leader of the House of Lords|Dep. Ldr (Lords)]]</small>}}\n|territorial_extent   = [[England and Wales]], [[Scotland]] and [[Northern Ireland]]<!-- [[British overseas territories]] is extended by the [[Privy Council]] under s.233(6) -->\n|amends               = {{startplainlist}}\n* [[Regulation of Investigatory Powers Act 2000]]\n* [[Terrorism Act 2006]]\n* [[Wireless Telegraphy Act 2006]]\n* [[Serious Crime Act 2007]]\n* [[Counter-Terrorism Act 2008]]\n* [[Policing and Crime Act 2009]]\n* [[Terrorism Prevention and Investigation Measures Act 2011]]\n* [[Health and Social Care Act 2012]]\n* [[Data Retention and Investigatory Powers Act 2014]]\n* [[Counter-Terrorism and Security Act 2015]]\n* [[Serious Crime Act 2015]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n|royal_assent         = 2nd July 2016\n|commencement         =\n|repeal_date          =\n|replaces             =\n|amendments           =\n|related_legislation  =\n|repealing_legislation=\n|status               = Current\n|original_text        =\n|legislation_history  =\n|use_new_UK-LEG       = yes\n|UK-LEG_title         =\n|revised_text         =\n|theyworkforyou       =\n|millbankhansard      =\n}}\nThe '''Investigatory Powers Act 2016''' (nicknamed the '''Snoopers' Charter''')<ref>{{cite web|last1=Griffin|first1=Andrew|title=UK spying laws: Government introduces law requiring WhatsApp and iMessage to break their own security|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/uk-spying-laws-uk-government-introduces-law-requiring-whatsapp-and-imessage-to-be-broken-a6905106.html|website=The Independent|publisher=Independent Print Limited|accessdate=12 March 2016|date=1 March 2016}}</ref> is an Act of the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] that has been passed by both Houses of Parliament,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/news/450403089/Investigatory-Powers-Bill-looks-set-to-become-law|title=Investigatory Powers Bill looks set to become law|author=Warwick Ashford|date=17 November 2016|work=computerweekly.com|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> and [[Queen Elizabeth II]] signified her [[Royal assent#United Kingdom|royal assent]] to the Investigatory Powers Act 2016 on 2nd July 2016.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/19/extreme-surveillance-becomes-uk-law-with-barely-a-whimper 'Extreme surveillance' becomes UK law with barely a whimper] Published by [[The Guardian]], 19 November 2016, accessed on the same day</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=editor|first1=Alan Travis Home affairs|title='Snooper's charter' bill becomes law, extending UK state surveillance|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/29/snoopers-charter-bill-becomes-law-extending-uk-state-surveillance|website=The Guardian|accessdate=29 November 2016|date=29 November 2016}}</ref> Its different parts come into force on various dates from 30 December 2016.<ref name=\":3\">[https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-act-bill-snoopers-charter-spying-law-powers-theresa-may-a7503616.html Investigatory Powers Act goes into force, putting UK citizens under intense new spying regime] Published by The Independent, 31 December 2016</ref> The Act comprehensively sets out and in limited respects expands the electronic surveillance powers of the [[UK intelligence community|UK Intelligence Community]] and police.<ref name=\":3\"/> It also aims to improve the safeguards on the exercise of those powers.<ref name=\"Guardian 27-4-2018\">{{Cite web |last=Cobain |first=Ian |title=UK has six months to rewrite snooper's charter, high court rules |website=The Guardian |language=en |date=27 April 2018 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/technology/2018/apr/27/snoopers-charter-investigatory-powers-act-rewrite-high-court-rules |access-date=2018-06-19}}</ref>\n\n== Drafting and scrutiny ==\nIn 2014 the [[Her Majesty's Government|UK government]] asked [[David Anderson (barrister)|David Anderson]], the [[Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation]], to review the operation and regulation of investigatory powers available to law enforcement and intelligence agencies, in particular the interception of communications and communications data, and to recommend change. This report<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daqc.co.uk/2015/06/11/a-question-of-trust-report-of-the-investigatory-powers-review/|title=A Question of Trust - Report of the Investigatory Powers Review (June 2015)|last=David Anderson|date=2015-06-11|website=David Anderson QC Lawyer London UK|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> was published in June 2015 and recommended a new law to clarify these powers.<ref>{{cite news|title=Surveillance powers: New law needed, says terror watchdog|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-33092894|accessdate=8 June 2016|work=BBC|date=11 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe Draft Investigatory Powers Bill was published in November 2015, with a large number of accompanying documents, and a [[Joint committee (legislative)|Joint Committee]] of the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|House of Commons]] and [[House of Lords]] was established to scrutinise the draft bill.<ref>{{cite web|title=Draft Bills 2015-16|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/bills-and-legislation/draft-bills/previous-sessions/draft-bills-2015-16/|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> Some parts of the bill referring to [[bulk personal datasets]] came into effect in November 2015, before parliamentary scrutiny began.<ref>{{cite web|title=Oral evidence: Draft Investigatory Powers Bill: Technology Issues HC573, Q.26 and Q.76|url=http://data.parliament.uk/writtenevidence/committeeevidence.svc/evidencedocument/science-and-technology-committee/investigatory-powers-bill-technology-issues/oral/24378.pdf|publisher=Parliament|accessdate=19 December 2015}}</ref> The Joint Committee published its pre-legislative scrutiny report in March 2016. The Government accepted the vast majority of its 198 recommendations,<ref>{{cite web|title=Government publishes Investigatory Powers Bill|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/joint-select/draft-investigatory-powers-bill/news-parliament-2015/government-response-published/|publisher=Parliament of the United Kingdom|date=2 March 2016|accessdate=19 November 2016}}</ref> together with the recommendations of two other parliamentary committees that had scrutinised the draft Bill, and the revised bill was introduced in the House of Commons,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill 2015-16 to 2016-17|url=http://services.parliament.uk/bills/2016-17/investigatorypowers.html|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref> where it was subject to debate by Members of Parliament.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: Remaining Stages|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/investigatory-powers-bill-commons-second-reading/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016|date=7 June 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: Committee Stage Report|journal=House of Commons Library|date=2 June 2016|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7578|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7578|accessdate=8 June 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2016 the House of Commons passed the Investigatory Powers Bill on its second reading by 281 votes to 15, moving the bill to the committee stage.<ref>Ryan Gallagher, [https://theintercept.com/2016/03/15/uk-parliament-debates-snoopers-charter/ U.K. Parliament Debates 'Snoopers' Charter], ''The Intercept (March 15, 2016).''</ref> The [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] and [[Scottish National Party]] abstained from the vote, while the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrats]] voted against it.<ref>Kelly Fiveash, [http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/03/investigatory-powers-bill-labour-and-snp-to-abstain-from-parliamentary-vote/ MPs vote in favour of Investigatory Powers Bill after Labour, SNP abstain &#91;Updated&#93;], ''Ars Technica'' (15 March 2016).</ref><ref>Rowena Mason, Anushka Asthana & Alan Travis, [https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/15/delay-investigatory-powers-bill-scrutiny-mps-second-reading-firms-campaigners 'Snooper's charter': Theresa May faces calls to improve bill to protect privacy], ''The Guardian'' (15 March 2016).</ref>\n\nAt the committee stage constitutional,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill constitutional implications assessed by Committee|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/lords-select/constitution-committee/news-parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-report/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=19 November 2016|date=11 July 2016}}</ref> technology,<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: technology issues inquiry|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/commons-select/science-and-technology-committee/inquiries/parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-bill-technology-issues-inquiry-launch-15-16/|publisher=Science and Technology Committee (House of Commons)}}</ref> and human rights issues were examined. The Labour Chair of the [[Joint Committee on Human Rights]], [[Harriet Harman]], said:\n{{Quote|text=The Bill provides a clear and transparent basis for powers already in use by the security and intelligence services, but there need to be further safeguards. Protection for MP communications from unjustified interference is vital, as it is for confidential communications between lawyers and clients, and for journalists\u2019 sources, the Bill must provide tougher safeguards to ensure that the Government cannot abuse its powers to undermine Parliament\u2019s ability to hold the Government to account.|author= Harriet Harman|source=<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill: direction of travel welcome, but improvements proposed|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/joint-select/human-rights-committee/news-parliament-2015/investigatory-powers-report-published-16-17/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=19 November 2016|date=2 June 2016}}</ref>}}\n\nAt this stage, at the insistence of the Labour Party, the [[Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation]] was commissioned to conduct a further review of the operational case for the bulk powers reserved under the Bill to the UK intelligence agencies: bulk interception, bulk collection of metadata, bulk equipment interference and the retention and use of bulk datasets. That review was conducted with the help of a small, security-cleared expert team, and together with 60 case studies, was published in August 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daqc.co.uk/2016/08/16/mass-surveillance-bulk-powers-review-august-2016/|title=Report of Bulk Powers Review, August 2016|last=David Anderson|date=2016-08-16|website=David Anderson QC Lawyer London UK|access-date=2017-07-06}}</ref> Like the 2014-15 reports of the [[Privacy and Civil Liberties Oversight Board|PCLOB]]<ref>https://pclob.gov/library/215-Report_on_the_Telephone_Records_Program.pdf (s215); https://pclob.gov/library/702-Report-2.pdf (s702).</ref> and [[National Academy of Sciences]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.nap.edu/catalog/19414/bulk-collection-of-signals-intelligence-technical-options|title=Bulk Collection of Signals Intelligence: Technical Options|last=Council|first=National Research|date=2015-01-15|isbn=9780309325202|language=en|doi=10.17226/19414}}</ref> in the USA, it is a significant information source for the utility of so-called [[mass surveillance]] techniques\n\nOn 16 November 2016 the [[House of Lords]] approved the final version of the Investigatory Powers Bill, leaving only the formality of [[Royal Assent]] to be completed before the Bill became law.<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Act imminent as peers clear path for UK super-snoop law|url=http://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2016/11/investigatory-powers-act-imminent-peers-clear-path-for-uk-super-snoop-law/|publisher=Ars Technica|accessdate=16 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 21 December 2016, the [[European Court of Justice]] (ECJ) declared that the generalised retention of certain types of personal data is unlawful, although little is known as to how this will affect the Investigatory Powers Act at this stage.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/law/2016/dec/21/eus-highest-court-delivers-blow-to-uk-snoopers-charter|title=EU's highest court delivers blow to UK snooper's charter|last=Bowcott|first=Owen|date=2016-12-21|work=|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-12-21|via=}}</ref> As of 29 January 2017, many sources have since reported on the Investigatory Powers Act as if it is currently in action.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.computerweekly.com/feature/Challenges-of-complying-with-the-Investigatory-Powers-Act|title=Challenges of complying with the Investigatory Powers Act|newspaper=ComputerWeekly|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-act-bill-snoopers-charter-spying-law-powers-theresa-may-a7503616.html|title=You just became subject to some of the most intense spying laws ever|date=2016-12-31|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nouse.co.uk/2017/01/29/nothing-to-hide-plenty-to-fear-from-prying-pm/|title=Nothing to hide, plenty to fear from prying PM|last=Bentley|first=Oscar|date=2017-01-29|website=Nouse|access-date=2017-01-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=91acc531-5b9c-483b-bd8f-2fd27619244a|title=Investigatory Powers Act 2016: How to Prepare For A Digital Age {{!}} Lexology|last=K|last2=Braamskamp|first2=L. Gates-Christine|access-date=2017-01-29|last3=Gilchrist|first3=rew W.|last4=Millward|first4=James G.}}</ref> Draft codes of practice laid out by the Home Office in February 2017 did not provide insight on the Government's communications data code of practise, as it was for the Court of Appeal to decide how to apply the December ruling of the ECJ on data retention in member states.I<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/investigatory-powers-act-2016-codes-of-practice|title=Investigatory Powers Act 2016: codes of practice - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk}}</ref> It was then reported in late February 2017 that the aspects of the Bill forcing [[communications service provider]]s to retain data had been \"[[mothball#Verb|mothballed]]\" due to the ECJ ruling on the \"general and indiscriminate\" retention of communications data being illegal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://arstechnica.co.uk/tech-policy/2017/02/investigatory-powers-law-missing-draft-communications-data-code/|title=UK forced to derail Snoopers' Charter blanket data slurp after EU ruling|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n== Provisions of the Act ==\nThe Act:<ref name=BBC051115>{{cite news|title=UK surveillance powers explained|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-34713435|accessdate=9 November 2015|work=BBC|date=5 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|title=Details of UK website visits 'to be stored for year'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-34715872|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=BBC|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=UK unveils powers to spy on web use, raising privacy fears|url=http://uk.reuters.com/article/2015/11/05/uk-britain-security-surveillance-idUKKCN0SS2RK20151105|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=Reuters|date=5 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Investigatory powers bill: the key points|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/04/investigatory-powers-bill-the-key-points|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite news|title=Surveillance Q&A: what web data is affected \u2013 and how to foil the snoopers|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/nov/04/surveillance-laws-theresa-may-snoopers-charter-internet-browsing-qa|accessdate=15 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* introduced new powers, and restated existing ones, for [[list of intelligence agencies of the United Kingdom|UK intelligence agencies]] and [[law enforcement in the United Kingdom|law enforcement]] to carry out targeted interception of [[telecommunication|communications]], bulk collection of [[communications data]], and bulk interception of communications;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Targeted Interception|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473739/Factsheet-Targeted_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Communications Data|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473755/Factsheet-Bulk_Communications_Data.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Interception|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473751/Factsheet-Bulk_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Communications Data|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473747/Factsheet-Communications_Data_General.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Personal Datasets|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473750/Factsheet-Bulk_Personal_Datasets.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015|postscript=none}}; {{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473756/Factsheet-Bill_Definitions.pdf|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bill Definitions|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* created an Investigatory Powers Commission (IPC) to oversee the use of all investigatory powers, alongside the oversight provided by the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] and the [[Investigatory Powers Tribunal]]. The IPC consists of a number of serving or former senior judges. It combined and replaced the powers of the Interception of Communications Commissioner, Intelligence Services Commissioner, and Chief Surveillance Commissioner;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Oversight|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473741/Factsheet-Oversight.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=FactsheetIPC>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Investigatory Powers Commission|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473744/Factsheet-Investigatory_Powers_Commission.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* established a requirement for a judge serving on the IPC to review warrants for accessing the content of communications and equipment interference authorised by a Secretary of State before they come into force;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Authorisation|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473758/Factsheet-Authorisation.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* required [[communication service providers]] (CSPs) to [[telecommunications data retention|retain]] UK internet users' \"Internet connection records\" \u2013 which websites were visited but not the particular pages and not the full browsing history \u2013 for one year;<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473745/Factsheet-Internet_Connection_Records.pdf|title=Factsheet \u2013 Internet Connection Records|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* allowed police, intelligence officers and other government department managers (listed below) to see the Internet connection records, as part of a targeted and filtered investigation, without a warrant;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Request filter|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473748/Factsheet-CD_Request_Filter.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* permitted the police and intelligence agencies to carry out targeted equipment interference, that is, hacking into computers or devices to access their data,<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Targeted Equipment Interference|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473740/Factsheet-Targeted_Equipment_Interference.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref> and bulk equipment interference for national security matters related to foreign investigations;<ref>{{cite web|title=Factsheet \u2013 Bulk Equipment Interference|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473751/Factsheet-Bulk_Interception.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n* placed a legal obligation on CSPs to assist with targeted interception of data, and communications and equipment interference in relation to an investigation; foreign companies are not required to engage in bulk collection of data or communications;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* maintained an existing requirement on CSPs in the UK to have the ability to remove encryption applied by the CSP; foreign companies are not required to remove encryption;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* put the [[Wilson Doctrine]] on a statutory footing for the first time as well as safeguards for other sensitive professions such as journalists, lawyers and doctors;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* provided local government with some investigatory powers, for example to investigate someone fraudulently claiming benefits, but not access to Internet connection records;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* created a new criminal offence for unlawfully accessing internet data;<ref name=BBC051115/>\n* created a new criminal offence for a CSP or someone who works for a CSP to reveal that data has been requested.<ref name=BBC051115/>\n\n=== Investigatory Powers Commissioner ===\nThe Act created the role of Investigatory Powers Commissioner to provide independent oversight of the use of investigatory powers by intelligence agencies, police forces and other public authorities. In March 2017 Lord Justice Sir [[Adrian Fulford]], a Court of Appeal judge, was appointed as first Commissioner for a three-year term. His office (IPCO)<ref name=ipco>{{cite web |url=https://www.ipco.org.uk/ |title=Investigatory Powers Commissioner's Office |publisher=Investigatory Powers Commissioner's Office |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref> will have fifteen senior judges as judicial commissioners, a technical advisory panel of scientific experts, and around 50 staff.<ref name=itv-20180616>{{cite news |url=https://www.itv.com/news/2018-06-16/who-is-the-investigatory-powers-commissioner-and-what-does-the-role-involve/ |title=Who is the Investigatory Powers Commissioner and what does the role involve? |work=ITV News |date=16 June 2018 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref><ref name=gov-20170303>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/investigatory-powers-commissioner-appointed-lord-justice-fulford |title=Investigatory Powers Commissioner appointed: Lord Justice Fulford |publisher=gov.uk |date=3 March 2017 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019 the [[Home Office]] blocked the appointment of Eric King as head of investigations at IPCO, citing national security grounds. King had previously been director of the Don\u2019t Spy On Us coalition, and deputy director of [[Privacy International]] for five years. King commented \"The problem, at its heart, is that there\u2019s a conflict as to whether my previous work and views are a positive or negative thing. They are both the reason I was hired and the reason my clearance was refused by the Home Office vetting team.\"<ref name=guardian-20190119>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/jan/19/edward-snowden-defender-eric-king-vetoed-top-surveillance-watchdog-job |title=Home Office under fire for blocking new spy watchdog |last=Townsend |first=Mark |newspaper=The Guardian |date=19 January 2019 |accessdate=26 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Authorities allowed to access Internet connection records ===\nList of authorities allowed to access Internet connection records without a warrant:<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/bills/lbill/2016-2017/0040/17040.pdf|title=Investigatory Powers Bill \u2014 Schedule 4 \u2014 Relevant public authorities and designated senior officers|last=|first=|date=|website=www.parliament.uk|publisher=Parliament|page=212|access-date=}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/ip-bill-law-details-passed|title=Snooper's Charter is set to become law: how the Investigatory Powers Bill will affect you|last=Burgess|first=Matt|newspaper=WIRED UK|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/gadgets-and-tech/news/investigatory-powers-bill-act-snoopers-charter-browsing-history-what-does-it-mean-a7436251.html|title=The list of organisations that will be allowed to view your entire internet history|date=2016-11-24|newspaper=The Independent|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-11-27}}</ref>\n{{colbegin}}\n* [[Metropolitan Police Service]]\n* [[City of London Police]]\n* Police forces maintained under section 2 of the Police Act 1996\n* [[Police Scotland|Police Service of Scotland]]\n* [[Police Service of Northern Ireland]]\n* [[British Transport Police]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence Police]]\n* [[Royal Navy Police]]\n* [[Royal Military Police]]\n* [[Royal Air Force Police]]\n* [[MI5|Security Service]]\n* [[Secret Intelligence Service]]\n* [[Government Communications Headquarters|GCHQ]]\n* [[Ministry of Defence]]\n* [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]]\n* [[Home Office]]\n* [[Ministry of Justice (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Justice]]\n* [[National Crime Agency]]\n* [[HM Revenue and Customs|HM Revenue & Customs]]\n* [[Department for Transport]]\n* [[Department for Work and Pensions]]\n* NHS trusts and foundation trusts in England that provide ambulance services\n* [[Common Services Agency for the Scottish Health Service|NHS National Services Scotland]]\n* [[Competition and Markets Authority]]\n* [[Criminal Cases Review Commission]]\n* [[Department for Communities|Department for Communities (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Department for the Economy|Department for the Economy (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Department of Justice (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Financial Conduct Authority]]\n* Fire and rescue authorities under the Fire and Rescue Services Act 2004\n* [[Food Standards Agency]]\n* [[Food Standards Scotland]]\n* [[Gambling Commission]]\n* [[Gangmasters and Labour Abuse Authority]]\n* [[Health and Safety Executive]]\n* [[Independent Police Complaints Commission]]\n* [[Information Commissioner's Office|Information Commissioner]]\n* [[NHS Business Services Authority]]\n* [[Northern Ireland Ambulance Service|Northern Ireland Ambulance Service Health and Social Care Trust]]\n* [[Northern Ireland Fire and Rescue Service|Northern Ireland Fire and Rescue Service Board]]\n* [[Health & Social Care Business Services Organisation|Health & Social Care Business Services Organisation (Northern Ireland)]]\n* [[Ofcom|Office of Communications]]\n* [[Office of the Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland|Police Ombudsman for Northern Ireland]]\n* [[Police Investigations and Review Commissioner]]\n* [[Scottish Ambulance Service Board]]\n* [[Scottish Criminal Cases Review Commission]]\n* [[Serious Fraud Office (United Kingdom)|Serious Fraud Office]]\n* [[Welsh Ambulance Service|Welsh Ambulance Services National Health Service Trust]]\n{{colend}}\n\n==Public debate==\n{{Quote box\n|quote= Does the UK really want the dubious honor of introducing powers deemed too intrusive by all other major democracies, joining the likes of China and Russia in collecting everyone's browsing habits?<ref name = \"Bloomberg most spied\"/>\n|source= \u2014Anne Jellema, head of the [[World Wide Web Foundation]]\n|align= right\n|width = 42%\n|bgcolor= AliceBlue\n|quoted= yes\n|salign= right\n}}\nThe draft Bill generated significant public debate about balancing intrusive powers and [[mass surveillance]] with the needs of the police and intelligence agencies to gain targeted access to information as part of their investigations.<ref>{{cite web|title=May wrong to say surveillance bill creates judicial authorisation for interception, says Liberty \u2013 live|url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/blog/live/2015/nov/04/surveillance-internet-snoopers-charter-may-plans-politics-live|publisher=The Guardian|accessdate=11 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Will Europe call the shots?|url=https://terrorismlegislationreviewer.independent.gov.uk/will-europe-call-the-shots/|accessdate=11 November 2015|publisher=Independent Reviewer of Terrorism Legislation|date=7 November 2015}}</ref> Although the [[Home Office]] said the Bill will be compatible with the [[European Convention on Human Rights]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill \u2013 European Convention on Human Rights Memorandum|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473763/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights_Memorandum.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015}}</ref> the content of the draft Bill has raised concerns about the impact on [[privacy]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Guardian view on the draft investigatory powers bill: snooper's charter 3.0|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2015/nov/02/the-guardian-view-on-the-draft-investigatory-powers-bill-snoopers-charter-30|accessdate=10 November 2015|work=The Guardian|date=2 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Investigatory Powers Bill - Privacy Impact Assessment|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/473778/Privacy-Impact-Assessment.pdf|publisher=Home Office|accessdate=15 November 2015|date=4 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nPrivacy campaigners say the bill clearly lays out the mass surveillance powers that would be at the disposal of the security services, and want it amended so that the surveillance is [[targeted surveillance|targeted]] and based on suspicion and argue that the powers are so sweeping, and the bill's language so general, that not just the security services but also government bodies will be able to analyse the records of millions of people even if they are not under suspicion.<ref name=ft1>{{cite web|last1=Vi\u00f1a|first1=Gonzalo|title=Surveillance: Taking liberties?|url=https://www.ft.com/content/1b7df076-57bb-11e6-9f70-badea1b336d4|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=2 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016 a report published by the [[Intelligence and Security Committee of Parliament]] recommended that the bill should focus on the right to privacy. Committee chairman, Conservative MP [[Dominic Grieve]], said: \"We have therefore recommended that the new legislation contains an entirely new part dedicated to overarching privacy protections, which should form the backbone of the draft legislation around which the exceptional powers are then built. This will ensure that privacy is an integral part of the legislation rather than an add-on.\" The committee also recommended that Class bulk personal dataset warrants are removed from the legislation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Internet monitoring bill 'must do more to protect privacy'|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-35531721|date=9 February 2016|publisher=BBC News|accessdate=9 February 2016}}</ref> Dominic Grieve later clarified the extent of these freedoms, \"the principle of the right to privacy against the state is maintained except if there is a good and sufficient reason why that should not happen.\"<ref>Third Reading of the Investigatory Powers Bill, Hansard, 6 June 2016.\n</ref>\n\nGavin E. L. Hall, a doctoral researcher at the [[University of Birmingham]], argues that public fear of the bill is not justified, writing that there are benefits to formally codifying in law what state security services can and cannot do and that \"While it may technically be possible under the bill to impugn individual freedom, [[John Bull]] has little to fear.\"<ref>{{cite news|author=Gavin E. L. Hall|title=Is the Snooper's Charter as Bad as You Think?|url=http://www.fairobserver.com/region/europe/is-the-snoopers-charter-as-bad-as-you-think-32300/|accessdate=11 March 2016|work=Fair Observer|date=10 March 2016}}</ref>\n\n''[[The Register]]'' argued the Act enshrines [[parallel construction]] in law and allows the state to lie about the origins of evidence in court, treating it as infallible, and prohibit the defendant from questioning it.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2016/12/06/parallel_construction_lies_in_english_courts/|title=The UK's Investigatory Powers Act allows the State to tell lies in court|first=Gareth Corfield 6 Dec 2016|last=at 09:00|website=www.theregister.co.uk}}</ref>\n\n[[Article 19]], a freedom of expression campaign group, criticized the Act as one of the most draconian pieces of surveillance legislation passed worldwide, warning that it \"offers a template for authoritarian regimes and seriously undermining the rights of its citizens to privacy and freedom of expression\".<ref>The Guardian, \"Global press freedom plunges to worst level this century\", 30 November 2017 https://www.theguardian.com/media/2017/nov/30/press-freedom-at-all-time-low-journalist-safety-article-19-v-dem-study</ref> The Chinese government cited the Snooper's Charter (officially the [[Draft Communications Data Bill]]) when defending its own intrusive anti-terrorism legislation.<ref name = \"Bloomberg most spied\">{{Cite web|title = 'Snooper's Charter' Would Make Brits Most Spied-Upon People|url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-02-11/-snooper-s-charter-would-make-brits-most-spied-upon-people|website = Bloomberg|access-date = 11 February 2016|first = Kristen|last = Schweizer|date = 11 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nRecent Wikileaks articles suggest that phone and digital device tracking both direct and indirect (eg FM radio blipping via Android exploit) also mentioned in Register posts by \"Anonymous Coward\" to covertly follow subjects have been used in the past but for operational reasons it is not clear if they are still used. The original poster has since decided to cooperate with the authorities and not comment further publicly on this subject, though the technique was independently rediscovered before the article in question was released.\n\n== Legal challenge and ruling ==\nIn November 2016, a petition demanding the law be repealed gained 100,000 signatures.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Titcomb|first1=James|title=Petition to repeal new surveillance powers reaches 100,000 signatures|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/11/28/petition-repeal-uks-new-surveillance-powers-reaches-100000-signatures/|newspaper=The Telegraph|accessdate=9 March 2017|date=30 November 2016}}</ref> In December 2016, pornographic media site [[xHamster]] redirected UK traffic to the petition.<ref>{{cite news|last1=McGoogan|first1=Cara|title=Porn website xHamster sends UK visitors to online petition against Snoopers' Charter|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/technology/2016/12/09/porn-website-xhamster-sends-uk-visitors-petition-against-snoopers/|newspaper=Telegraph|accessdate=9 March 2017|date=9 December 2016}}</ref> In March 2017, [[Liberty (advocacy group)|Liberty]], a human rights organisation, raised \u00a350,000 via crowd funding towards legal actions against the bill. Silkie Carlo, policy officer at Liberty, said: {{quote|The powers we're fighting undermine everything that's core to our freedom and democracy \u2014 our right to protest, to express ourselves freely and to a fair trial, our free press, privacy and cybersecurity. But with so much public support behind us, we're hopeful we will be able to persuade our courts to restrain the more authoritarian tendencies of this Government.|Silkie Carlo, policy officer at Liberty<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hopping|first1=Clare|title=Liberty launches legal challenge against Investigatory Powers Act|url=http://www.itpro.co.uk/it-legislation/28251/liberty-launches-legal-challenge-against-investigatory-powers-act|publisher=IT Pro|accessdate=9 March 2017}}</ref>}}\n\nIn April 2018 the UK high court ruled that the Investigatory Powers Act violates EU law.<ref name=\"Guardian 27-4-2018\"/> The government had until 1 November 2018 to amend the legislation.<ref>{{cite web |last=Carey |first=Scott |title=The Snoopers' Charter: Everything you need to know about the Investigatory Powers Act |website=Computerworld UK |date=27 April 2018 |publisher=[[International Data Group|IDG UK]] |url=https://www.computerworlduk.com/security/draft-investigatory-powers-bill-what-you-need-know-3629116/ |accessdate=25 August 2018}}</ref> On 31 October 2018 The Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2018/1123/made/data.htm|title=The Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018|website=www.legislation.gov.uk|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref> came into force to address this ruling. These regulations increased the threshold for accessing communications data only for the purposes of serious crime (defined as offences which are capable of being sentenced to imprisonment for a term of 12 months or more) and requires that authorities consult an independent Investigatory Powers Commissioner before requesting data. The regulations also included a loophole where rapid approval can be made internally without independent approval but with a three day expiry and with subsequent review by the independent body. Most debates about the regulations have been about the definition of \"serious crime\" with many arguing that the threshold should be at three years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/lords/?id=2018-10-30a.1289.1|title=Data Retention and Acquisition Regulations 2018 - Motion to Approve: 30 Oct 2018: House of Lords debates|website=TheyWorkForYou|language=en|access-date=2019-01-10}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Bill on Intelligence]] (French law)\n* [[Draft Communications Data Bill]], a draft bill produced for consultation in 2012 but never introduced to Parliament\n* ''{{lang|de|[[Gesetz zur Beschr\u00e4nkung des Brief-, Post- und Fernmeldegeheimnisses]]}}'' (German law)\n* [[Mass surveillance in the United Kingdom]]\n* [[Patriot Act]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2016/25/contents/enacted Full text of the act as enacted] at [[legislation.gov.uk]]\n* {{cite web|title=Draft Investigatory Powers Bill|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/draft-investigatory-powers-bill|publisher=Home Office}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Draft Investigatory Powers Bill|journal=House of Commons Library|date=19 November 2015|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7371|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7371|accessdate=8 June 2016}}\n* {{cite journal|title=Investigatory Powers Bill|journal=House of Commons Library|date=11 March 2016|issue=Commons Briefing papers CBP-7518|url=http://researchbriefings.parliament.uk/ResearchBriefing/Summary/CBP-7518|accessdate=8 June 2016}}\n* {{cite web|title=Have your say on the Investigatory Powers Bill|url=http://www.parliament.uk/business/news/2016/march/have-your-say-on-the-investigatory-powers-bill/|publisher=UK Parliament|accessdate=8 June 2016|date=16 March 2016}}\n\n[[Category:Surveillance]]\n[[Category:Government databases in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Law enforcement techniques]]\n[[Category:Counter-terrorism]]\n[[Category:Mass surveillance]]\n[[Category:National security policies]]\n[[Category:Surveillance databases]]\n[[Category:2015 in British law]]\n[[Category:Home Office (United Kingdom)]]\n[[Category:Government Communications Headquarters]]\n[[Category:2015 in British politics]]\n[[Category:Data laws of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:United Kingdom Acts of Parliament 2016]]\n", "name_user": "Chrism", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eDrafting and scrutiny", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Investigatory_Powers_Act_2016"}
{"title_page": "House of Representatives (Netherlands)", "text_new": "{{more citations needed|date=June 2015}}\n{{Infobox legislature\n| background_color   = #121469\n| name               = House of Representatives\n| native_name        = {{native name|nl|Tweede Kamer der Staten-Generaal|icon=no}}\n| native_name_lang   =\n| transcription_name =\n| legislature        = [[States General of the Netherlands]]\n| coa_pic            = Coat of arms of the Tweede Kamer.svg\n| coa_res            =\n| coa_alt            =\n| logo_pic           =\n| logo_res           =\n| logo_alt           =\n| house_type         = Lower House\n| body               =\n| houses             =\n| term_limits        =\n| foundation         = <!-- {{Start date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| disbanded          =\n| preceded_by        =\n| succeeded_by       =\n| new_session        =\n| leader1_type       = [[Speaker of the House of Representatives (Netherlands)|Speaker]]\n| leader1            = [[Khadija Arib]]\n| party1             = [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]\n| election1          = 13 January 2016\n| leader2_type       = First Deputy Speaker\n| leader2            = [[Ockje Tellegen]]\n| party2             = [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]]\n| election2          = 31 October 2017\n| seats              = 150\n| house1             =\n| house2             =\n| structure1         = Tweede Kamer 2017.svg\n| structure1_res     = 250px\n| structure1_alt     = \n| structure2         =\n| structure2_res     =\n| structure2_alt     =\n| political_groups1  = '''[[Third Rutte cabinet|Government]] (75)'''<ref>{{cite web|title=Netherlands: Coalition deal reached after 209 days|url=http://p.dw.com/p/2lUq6|website=DW|publisher=Deutsche Welle|accessdate=10 October 2017|date=9 October 2017}}</ref>\n* {{Color box|{{People's Party for Freedom and Democracy/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]] (32)\n* {{Color box|{{Christian Democratic Appeal/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Christian Democratic Appeal|CDA]] (19)\n* {{Color box|{{Democrats 66/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Democrats 66|D66]] (19)\n* {{Color box|{{ChristianUnion/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[ChristianUnion|CU]] (5)\n'''Opposition parties (75)'''\n* {{Color box|{{Party for Freedom/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Party for Freedom|PVV]] (20)\n* {{Color box|{{GroenLinks/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[GroenLinks|GL]] (14)\n* {{Color box|{{Socialist Party (Netherlands)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|SP]] (14)\n* {{Color box|{{Labour Party (Netherlands)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|PvdA]] (9)<ref name=PvdA2020>Despite being in the opposition, the [[Ministry of Health, Welfare and Sport|Minister for Medical Care]] is a member of the PvdA.</ref> \n* {{Color box|{{50PLUS/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[50PLUS]] (4)\n* {{Color box|{{Party for the Animals/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Party for the Animals|PvdD]] (4)\n* {{Color box|{{Reformed Political Party/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Reformed Political Party|SGP]] (3)\n* {{Color box|{{Denk (Dutch political party)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Denk (Dutch political party)|DENK]] (3)\n* {{Color box|{{Forum for Democracy (Netherlands)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Forum for Democracy|FvD]] (2)\n* {{Color box|{{Independent (politician)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} [[Independent politician|Independent]] (2)\n| committees1        =\n| joint_committees   =\n| voting_system1     = [[Elections in the Netherlands|Party-list proportional representation]] [[D'Hondt method]]\n| last_election1     = [[2017 Dutch general election|15 March 2017]]\n| next_election1     = [[Next Dutch general election|17 March 2021]]\n| session_room       = Tweede kamer.jpg\n| session_res        = 250px\n| session_alt        = The Second Chamber sits in the Binnenhof in The Hague\n| meeting_place      = [[Binnenhof]] <br/> [[The Hague]], <br/> [[Netherlands]]\n| website            = [http://www.houseofrepresentatives.nl House of Representatives] <br/> [http://www.tweedekamer.nl Tweede Kamer]\n| footnotes          =\n| motto              =\n}}\n\nThe '''House of Representatives''' ({{Lang-nl|Tweede Kamer der Staten-Generaal}}, pronounced {{IPA-nl|\u02c8t\u028be\u02d0d\u0259 \u02c8ka\u02d0m\u0259r d\u025br \u02c8sta\u02d0t\u0259(n) \u02cc\u0263e\u02d0n\u0259\u02c8ra\u02d0l||2e_kamer.ogg}}; commonly referred to as the ''{{Lang|nl|Tweede Kamer}}'', literally '''Second Chamber''') is the [[lower house]] of the [[Bicameralism|bicameral]] [[parliament]] of the [[Netherlands]], the [[States General of the Netherlands|States General]], the other one being the [[Senate (Netherlands)|Senate]]. It has 150 seats which are filled through [[Elections in the Netherlands|elections]] using a [[party-list proportional representation]]. It sits in the [[Binnenhof]] in [[The Hague]].\n\n==Name==\nAlthough this body is called the \"House of Representatives\" in English, this is not a direct translation of its Dutch name, the \"Second Chamber\" or more colloquially just the \"Chamber\". Rather than \"representatives\" (''afgevaardigden''), members of the House are referred to as ''Tweede Kamerlid'' (\"member of the Second Chamber\").\n\nAalissa from Urban Academy Charter School is a hoe she likes other girls mans she can't fight and her hair was the reason animals a going extinct lord Jesus help bless her with so miricle drops please and thank you\n\n==Elections==\nThe normal term of the House of Representatives is four years. Elections are called when the government loses parliament's confidence, the governing coalition breaks down, the term of the House of Representatives expires or when no governing coalition can be formed.\n\n===Parties===\n{{main|Political parties of the Netherlands}}\nAnybody eligible to vote in the Netherlands also has the right to establish a [[political party]] and contest elections for the House of Representatives. Parties wanting to take part must register 43 days before the elections, supplying a nationwide list of at most 50 candidates (80 if the party already has more than 15 seats). Parties that do not have any sitting candidates in the House of Representatives must also pay a deposit (11,250 euro for the November 2006 elections, for all districts together) and provide 30 signatures of support from residents of each of the 20 electoral districts in which they want to collect votes.\n\n===Party lists===\nThe candidate lists are placed in the hands of the voters at least 14 days before the election. Each candidate list is numbered, with the person in the first position known as the ''[[lijsttrekker]]'' (\"list puller\"). The lijsttrekker is usually appointed by the party to lead its election campaign, and is almost always the party's political leader and candidate for [[Prime Minister of the Netherlands|Prime Minister]]. Parties may choose to compete with different candidate lists in each of the 20 electoral districts, but as seats are allocated on national rather than district level, most parties have almost identical lists in all districts with candidates running nationwide. Only large parties usually have some regional candidates at the bottom of their lists. From 1973 until abolition in June 2017 it was possible for two or more parties to combine their separate lists to increase the chance of winning a remainder seat. This was known as a '[[list combination]]' or ''Lijstverbinding'' / ''lijstencombinatie''.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.volkskrant.nl/binnenland/fenomeen-politieke-lijstverbinding-sneuvelt-in-eerste-kamer~a4501654/ | title=Fenomeen politieke lijstverbinding sneuvelt in Eerste Kamer | author=Gijs Herdersche\u00ea | date=20 June 2017 | publisher=Volkskrant}}</ref>\n\n===Registration and voting===\nCitizens of the [[Kingdom of the Netherlands]] aged 18 or over have the right to vote, with the exception of 1) prisoners serving a term of more than one year 2) those who have been declared incapable by court because of insanity 3) residents of Aruba, Cura\u00e7ao and Sint Maarten, unless they have spent ten years residing in the Netherlands or work for the Dutch civil service.<ref>{{cite|url=https://www.kiesraad.nl/verkiezingen/tweede-kamer/stemmen/kiesgerechtigdheid | title=Kiesgerechtigdheid | publisher=Government of the Netherlands | accessdate=December 2, 2018}}</ref> Eligible citizens resident in the Netherlands are able to vote if they are registered on a municipal population register (''Basisregistratie Personen''). Eligible citizens outside the Netherlands can permanently register to vote at the municipality of [[The Hague]], provided they have a current Dutch passport or identity card.\n\nA single vote can be placed on any one candidate. Many voters select one of the lijsttrekkers ([[Jan Peter Balkenende]], for example, received 2,198,114 of the CDA's 2,608,573 votes in the November 2006 elections), but alternatively a preference vote may be made for a candidate lower down the list.\n\n===Allocation of seats===\n[[File:The Hague car-free city-centre 31.JPG|thumb|right|220px|Exterior of the House of Representatives]]\nOnce the election results are known, the seats are allocated to the parties. The number of valid national votes cast is divided by 150, the number of seats available, to give a threshold for each seat (the ''kiesdeler''); 1/150th is approximately 0.67% of the valid votes. Each party's number of votes is divided by this threshold, and rounded down to the nearest whole number, to give an initial number of seats equal to the number of times the threshold was reached.<ref name=\"wetten.nl 2019\">{{cite web | title=Kieswet, Hoofdstuk P | website=wetten.nl | date=2019-02-22 | url=https://wetten.overheid.nl/jci1.3:c:BWBR0004627&afdeling=II&hoofdstuk=P&z=2019-02-22&g=2019-02-22 | language=nl | access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref> Any party that received fewer votes than the threshold fails to gain representation in the House of Representatives. After the initial seats are allocated, the remainder seats are allocated among the parties that received at least one seat, using the [[D'Hondt method]] of largest averages. This system slightly favours the larger parties. Since parties that received fewer votes than required to obtain one whole seat are not eligible for remainder seats, there is a de facto [[election threshold]] of 0.67%.<ref name=\"Kiesraad.nl 2016\">{{cite web | title=Kiesdrempel, kiesdeler en voorkeurdrempel | website=Kiesraad.nl | date=2016-04-22 | url=https://www.kiesraad.nl/verkiezingen/tweede-kamer/uitslagen/kiesdrempel-kiesdeler-en-voorkeurdrempel | language=nl | access-date=2019-07-07}}</ref> This threshold is one of the lowest for national parliaments in the world, and there are usually multiple parties winning seats with 2% or less of the vote. Any party that did not have seats in the House at the time of the election will have its deposit refunded if it receives more than 75% of the threshold (1/200th of the vote).\n\nOnce the number of seats allocated to each party is known, in general they are allocated to candidates in the order that they appear on the party's list. (Hence, before the elections, the candidates near the top may be described as in an electable position, depending on the number of seats that the party is likely to obtain.) At this stage, however, the preference votes are also taken into account. Any candidate receiving more than one quarter of the threshold on personal preference votes (the 'preference threshold' or ''voorkeursdrempel'', 0.1675% of the total number of valid votes), is considered elected in their own right, leapfrogging candidates higher on the list. In the November 2006 elections, only one candidate received a seat exclusively through preference votes, while 26 other candidates reaching the preference threshold were already elected based on their position on the list. If a candidate cannot take up the position in parliament (e.g., if they become a [[Political minister|minister]], decide not to enter parliament, or later resign) then the next candidate on the list takes their place.\n\n===Formation of governing coalition===\nAfter all seats are allocated, a series of negotiations take place in order to form a government that, usually, commands a majority in the chamber. Since 2012, the House of Representatives appoints a \"scout\" to ask the major party leaders about prospective coalitions. On the basis of the scout's interviews, the House of Representatives then appoints an [[Cabinet of the Netherlands#Formation|informateur]], who checks out possible coalitions, and [[Cabinet of the Netherlands#Formation|formateur]], who leads negotiations (in previous years the informateur and formateur were appointed by the [[Monarchy of the Netherlands|monarch]]). It typically takes a few months before the formateur is ready to accept a royal invitation to form a government and become prime minister. All cabinet members must resign from parliament, as the constitution does not allow a cabinet member to hold a seat in the House of Representatives.\n\nDue to the nationwide party-list system and the low election threshold, a typical House of Representatives has ten or more factions represented. Such fragmentation makes it nearly impossible for one party to win the 76 seats needed for a majority in the House of Representatives. Indeed, since the current party-list proportional representation system was introduced in 1918, no party has even approached the number of seats that are even theoretically needed to govern alone, let alone win enough for an outright majority. The highest proportion of seats won by a single party since then has been 54 out of 150, obtained by the CDA in 1986 and 1989. Between 1891 and 1897, the [[Liberal Union (Netherlands)|Liberal Union]] was the last party to have an absolute majority of seats in the House of Representatives. All Dutch cabinets since then have been coalitions of two or more parties.\n\n==House of Representatives offices==\nThe buildings that house the individual offices of the Members of the House of Representatives and conference rooms for closed-door party meetings are all located on the [[Binnenhof]]. The main buildings of the old [[Ministry of Justice and Security (Netherlands)|Ministry of Justice]] and Ministry of Colonial Affairs are used as accommodations.\n\n<gallery mode=packed>\nFile:Den Haag - Plein 2a.JPG|The old Ministry of Justice building\nFile:Den Haag - Plein 1.JPG|The old Ministry of Colonial Affairs building\nFile:Rm17532.JPG|Grand Hotel Central building\nFile:Binnenhof, The Hague 1828.jpg|Binnenhof Building C\nFile:Binnenhof, The Hague 1873.jpg|Binnenhof Building 1A\n</gallery>\n\n{{Col-begin}}\n{{Col-5}}\n* Old Ministry of Justice building:\n** [[Christian Democratic Appeal]]\n** [[Democrats 66]]\n** [[Forum for Democracy (Netherlands)|Forum for Democracy]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/04/06/nieuwkomers-denk-en-forum-krijgen-geen-andere-plek-in-zaal-tweede-kamer-7959181-a1553388|title=Nieuwkomers Denk en Forum krijgen geen andere plek in zaal Tweede Kamer|date=2017-04-06|accessdate=2017-11-04|work=NRC Handelsblad|language=nl}}</ref>\n{{Col-5}}\n* Old Ministry of Colonial Affairs building:\n** [[GroenLinks]]\n** [[Labour Party (Netherlands)|Labour Party]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.ad.nl/politiek/verhuizing-kamer-lastige-puzzel-door-eisen-kleine-partijen~a38aea52/|title=Verhuizing Kamer lastige puzzel door eisen kleine partijen|date=2017-04-07|accessdate=2017-11-04|work=Algemeen Dagblad|language=nl}}</ref>\n** [[Christian Union (Netherlands)|Christian Union]]\n** [[Party for the Animals]]\n{{Col-5}}\n* Grand Hotel Central:\n** [[Party for Freedom]]\n** [[50PLUS]]\n{{Col-5}}\n* Binnenhof Building C:\n** [[Socialist Party (Netherlands)|Socialist Party]]\n** [[Reformed Political Party]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/06/02/reken-niet-zomaar-op-de-sgp-10889477-a1561532|title=\u2018Reken niet zomaar op de SGP\u2019|date=2017-06-02|accessdate=2017-11-04|work=NRC Handelsblad|language=nl}}</ref>\n** [[Denk (political party)|Denk]]\n{{Col-5}}\n* Binnenhof Building 1A:\n** [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2017/03/21/pijnlijk-gepuzzel-aan-het-binnenhof-7490966-a1551246|title=Partijen onderhandelen over werkplek - wie eindigt op zolder?|date=2017-03-21|accessdate=2017-11-04|work=NRC Handelsblad|language=nl}}</ref>\n{{Col-end}}\n\n==Composition==\n===Historical compositions===\n{{Main|Historic composition of the House of Representatives of the Netherlands}}\n[[File:Dutchparlseats2.png|thumb|Representation per party, between 1946 and 2018]]\n\nUntil 1956, there were 100 seats. This was expanded to 150 seats, which is the current number.\n\nTo give an overview of the history of the House of Representatives, the figure on the right shows the seat distribution in the House from the first general elections after World War II (1946) to the current situation. The left-wing parties are towards the bottom, the Christian parties in the centre, with the right-wing parties towards the top. Occasionally, single-issue (or narrow-focus) parties have arisen, and these are shown at the extreme top. Vertical lines indicate general elections. Although these are generally held every four years, the resulting coalition governments do not always finish their term without a government crisis, which is often followed by fresh elections. Hence the frequent periods shorter than four years.\n\n===Current situation===\n{{Main|List of members of the House of Representatives of the Netherlands, 2017\u2013present}}\n\nThe [[2017 Dutch general election|Dutch general election of 2017]] was held on Wednesday, 15 March 2017, and followed the call for new elections after the [[Second Rutte cabinet]] had completed its four-year term. The new Members of the House of Representatives were installed on 23 March 2017. Four parties were required to form a coalition with a simple majority (76 seats). Rutte's [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]], as well as the [[Christian Democratic Appeal|CDA]], [[Democrats 66|D66]] and [[ChristianUnion|CU]] parties, later agreed to form a governing coalition with the required one-seat majority after the longest time since an election took place, 209 days, surpassing the previous record of 208 days set after the [[1977 Dutch general election|1977 general elections]].\n\n{{Politics of the Netherlands}}\n{{Dutch general election, 2017}}\n\n==Parliamentary leaders==\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n!colspan=2|Portrait\n!Name\n!Party\n!Service as Parliamentary leader\n!Service as a Member of <br/> the House of Representatives\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{People's Party for Freedom and Democracy/meta/color}};\"|\n| [[File:Klaas Dijkhoff 2015 (2).jpg|120px|Klaas Dijkhoff]]\n| <small>[[Doctor (title)|Dr.]]</small> <br/> [[Klaas Dijkhoff]] <br/> <small>(born 1981)</small>\n| [[People's Party for Freedom and Democracy|VVD]]\n| 25 October 2017 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|2017|10|25}})</small>\n| 23 March 2017 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|2017|03|23}})</small> <br/> <br/> 17 June 2010 \u2013 <br/> 20 March 2015 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|2010|06|17|2015|03|20}})</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Party for Freedom/meta/color}};\"|\n| [[File:Geert Wilders op Prinsjesdag 2014 (cropped2).jpg|120px|Geert Wilders]]\n| [[Geert Wilders]] <br/> <small>(born 1963)</small>\n| [[Party for Freedom|PVV]]'''\n| 30 November 2006 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|2006|11|30}})</small>\n| 26 July 2002 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|2002|06|26}})</small> <br/> <br/> 25 August 1998 \u2013 <br/> 23 May 2002 <br/> <small>({{Age in years and days|1998|08|25|2002|05|23}})</small>\n|-\n| style=\"background:{{Christian Democratic Appeal/meta/color}};\"|\n| [[File:Pieter Heerma (2017).jpg|120